name: Lakeside School
description: Middle school: Computer 5, Computer 6 and Computer 7 - integrated technology courses in the middle school for 5th, 6th and 7th grades. Focus is on learning organizational and time management skills through programming. High School: Computer science 1 - an introductory course focused on building skills and confidence with computers and programming CS 2/3 - Java based, fast paced, AP level computer science sequence CS 4 - Advanced, project based, post AP class. 3D modeling and printing - a project based hands on course in 3D printing. Summer school: CS1 - Computer science 1 - an introductory course focused on building skills and confidence with computers and programming (3 week all day intensive course). name: University of Washington Summer Youth Program
description: UW Summer Youth Programs offer unique, hands-on enrichment opportunities for children and teens. Students can enroll in full day camps and half-day short courses led by highly qualified and experienced instructors. Camps and courses cover a wide range of topics designed to appeal to students who have interests in STEM (science, technology, engineering and math), computer programming, the visual and performing arts, and humanities.
languages: Computer game programming for middle school | Java | Kodu | Scratch

name: Eckstein Middle School
description: A semester long exploration of computer science and technology that emphasizes problem solving and algorithmic thinking. Each semester explores a different topic, so students may repeat this course as desired. Some topics include computer programming, web development, robotics, hardware and networking. Every semester will explore human/computer interaction, and the legal, social and ethical issues surrounding technology.

name: Silicon Valley CoderDojo
description: At CoderDojo, young people, ages 7-17, learn how to code, develop websites, apps, programs, games and more. Dojos are set up, run by and taught at by volunteers. CoderDojo also puts a strong emphasis on open source and free software environments. Look for free tickets, and event announcements, on Eventbrite
languages: HTML | Java | Javascript | Mobile Apps (Android) | Mobile Apps (iOS) | Python | Ruby | Scratch

name: CodeEd at the Community Charter School of Cambridge
description: CodeEd teaches computer science to girls in underserved communities, starting in middle school. Started in 2010, we train volunteer teachers with technical backgrounds, provide them with curriculum, support and computers, and match them with our education partners.

name: Dev Bootcamp (San Francisco)
description: Dev Bootcamp, founded in 2011, is the first short-term programming bootcamp designed to train world-class junior web developers and software engineers. Students spend 700+ hours over 9 weeks deliberately practicing the fundamentals of software engineering and web development using Ruby, Rails, HTML, CSS, SQL, and JavaScript. Our focus is on graduating engineers first and Rails-proficient web developers second. Within two months of graduation 90%+ of the students looking for jobs receive an offer with a median salary of $75k. Our alumni work at companies like Exec, Hipmunk, 1000memories, ThoughtBot, Pivotal Labs, TapJoy, Ouya, and The Climate Corporation. Think of it as a bootcamp-ified Montessori school or an apprenticeship of steroids. Some words from our students: * "DBC is the best learning environment that I have ever been in." (Student, Fall 2012) * "Dev Bootcamp has simply changed my entire life." (Student, Summer 2012) * "Dev Bootcamp was pretty much the best, most compact learning experience of my life." (Student, Summer 2012)

name: University of Washington Computer Science & Engineering
description: Our summer camps introduce middle and high school students to computer science (http://camps.cs.washington.edu/). Our open house brings in hundreds of students and their parents to try hands-on activities related to computing (http://www.cs.washington.edu/openhouse) We host programming competitions for high school students (http://www.pscsta.org/p/student-programming-contests.html) and visit local classrooms. Our summer teacher workshops bring together over 70 local instructors (http://cs4hs.cs.washington.edu/).
languages: HTML | Mobile apps (android) | Processing | Python | Scratch

name: Code Fellows
description: At Code Fellows, we believe in hands-on training. Our full-time bootcamps have formal instruction in the mornings followed by co-working in the afternoons. Our instructors sit side-by-side with the students as they learn to code. We prepare students to enter the job market through interview coaching, guest lectures, and introductions to local companies. We offer a rotating set of bootcamps teaching Ruby on Rails, Javascript, Python, and iOS, as well as evening workshops. For a complete listing, please visit our website.
languages: HTML | Javascript | Mobile Apps (iOS) | Python | Ruby

Within the group we see each other as equals and are able to learn from our unique experiences. We strive to deliver content that appeals to our members that are just beginning their journey into technology and those that have been on their journey for a while.

All classes are individualized for each student so they can go at their own pace and start anytime. Kids come 2 hours a week (once or twice per week) and we encourage learning at home as well by providing all necessary resources and remote help anytime a kid needs assistance. Hours are Monday-Friday 2-6:30pm and Saturdays 8am-12pm.

description: L.D.College of Engineering, Ahmedabad is a premier engineering college in Gujarat State set with the objectives of imparting higher education in various fields of engineering. Sheth Shri Kasturbhai Lalbhai established institute in 1948 with generous donation. It is situated adjacent to Gujarat University and at nucleus of various national level institutes like PRL, ATIRA, ISRO, IIM etc. The campus consists of buildings for various departments, offices, hostels and library with 64,565 sq.meter builtup area. The institute made a modest start with 75 students for undergraduate programs in 1948, post graduate programs in 1954. At present institute runs 14 undergraduate, 17-post graduate and 4 part-time programs.

Electives in Computer Science in the Upper School focus on programming Java. name: Nashville Software School
description: Nashville Software School (NSS) is a place where a person with aptitude, motivation, passion and commitment can learn the craft of software development. A place where you can get a running start down the path to a life-long career in technology and software development. In fact its more than a running start, it's a blast down the runway with afterburners. Our intensive training and apprenticeship program dramatically accelerates learning about and access to the world of software development. Give us six months and we'll prepare you for an entry-level software developer job.

name: Ladies Learning Code
description: Ladies Learning Code is a Toronto-based not-for-profit organization that runs workshops for women (and men) who want to learn beginner-friendly programming and other technical skills in a social and collaborative way. We also have chapters in Vancouver and Ottawa.

name: Girls Learning Code
format_description: Tech Camps, Workshops and Clubs for girls between 9-13
description: We're looking for Toronto's most creative 9-13 year old girls. Know anyone like that? Introducing Girls Learning Code - tech camps, workshops and events for girls who want to change the world. Founded by the same women who introduced Ladies Learning Code in 2011, Girls Learning Code is less about code and more about changing the world  through teamwork, creativity, and, of course, technology. At our camps and workshops, Torontos most creative 9-13 year old girls join us to participate in the citys only all-girls technology camp and workshops. This program experience is designed to help girls see technology in a whole new light  as a medium for self-expression, and as a means for changing the world. Program Objectives: We help girls: 1. Discover a passion for learning about technology 2. Experience the satisfaction that comes from being a builder  not just consumer  of the web and technology 3. Become more confident and self-assured 4. Develop a willingness to try new things 5. Increase their knowledge of technology-related careers all while having fun! What Makes Girls Learning Code Different? Girls Learning Code has been designed specifically with girls in mind, by the team who founded Ladies Learning Code. When developing plans and curriculum for our camps and workshops, we keep in mind a recurrent theme in research on gender and technology: girls approach the computer as a tool useful primarily for what it can do; boys more often view the computer as a toy or an extension of the self. Thus, the themes revolve around Changing the World and technology is used as the means, not the end.
languages: 3d printing and more | Arduino | HTML | Javascript | Mobile apps (android) | Photo editing | Python | Robotics | Ruby | Scratch | Technology careers | Video editing | Web design

Thus, the themes revolve around Changing the World and technology is used as the means, not the end.

name: UC Berkeley
description: CS10, The Beauty and Joy of Computing, is an exciting new course offered by the UC Berkeley EECS Dept. Computing has changed the world in profound ways. It has opened up wonderful new ways for people to connect, design, research, play, create, and express themselves. However, just using a computer is only a small part of the picture. The real transformative and empowering experience comes when one learns how to program the computer, to translate ideas into code. This course will teach students how to do exactly that, using BYOB and Snap! (based on Scratch), one of the friendliest programming languages ever invented. It's purely graphical, which means programming involves simply dragging blocks around, and building bigger blocks out of smaller blocks. But this course is far more than just learning to program. We'll focus on some of the "Big Ideas" of computing, such as abstraction, design, recursion, concurrency, simulations, and the limits of computation. We'll show some beautiful applications of computing that have changed the world, talk about the history of computing, and where it will go in the future. Throughout the course, relevance will be emphasized: relevance to the student and to society.

description: Coding Dojo, based in Silicon Valley CA, provides a 9 week bootcamp training for aspiring web developers. If you get a job out of the program, you receive a full refund of your tuition. At our offices in the heart of Silicon Valley, you'll learn everything from HTML to Ruby on Rails amidst the campuses of Google, Apple, and countless startups. Students will meet from 9am-6pm, Monday-Friday, and learn to breath, eat (we provide lunch, dinner and healthy snacks), and dream about coding. You'll have the opportunity to work closely with similarly driven people, attend a variety of different coding meetups, and frequently hear from prominent guest speakers, CTOs, and other generally cool developers. After 9 weeks of intense training, we'll have a demo day where recruiters, hiring managers, and startups will be invited to interview and hire you. Over the last 2 years, CodingDojo has refined training for developers, allowing us to take someone new to programming to where they can build advanced web applications in PHP, Javascript, Ruby, Node.JS, SQL database, all in just a few months. The training is rigorous, and only for those serious about learning to code, and serious about getting a job as a web developer.

name: Chandler High School
description: Our Informational Technology program is under our state's Career and Technical Education program. It is broken into 4 options. Our introductory class (Fundamentals of Informational Technology or F.I.T.) covers each of these for a quarter of the year. They are computer maintenance, software engineering, web design, and networking. Students who continue have the option of taking a computer maintenance class in preperation for taking the CompTia A+ certification exam. This class covers both hardware and operating systems. They also refurbish used computers through the STudents Recycling Used Technology program. Another option is our Software Engineering I and IB/AP Java classes. Both of these classes cover the Java curriculum required for the AP exam and our state CTE Software Development exam. An introduction to creating Android apps is also taught. Our one other option is robotics. We have it as both a class and a club. The curriculum covers both hardware used such as motors, transmissions, speed controllers, programmable control boards, pneumatics, and design based learning concepts as well as java programming. Students can choose to work independently on other languages for doing vision processing for autonomous programming as well. The club meets every Wednesday afterschool from 2:15 to 4:00. During our FIRST Robotics season 6 week build time we will also come in on Saturdays for the whole day. Once school is out for the summer, we host the National Underwater Robotics Challenge or NURC. That gives us the challenge of building underwater robots as well. This last year we used an Arduino control board with an ethernet shield to talk to the surface. New programming language challenges always!

description: The Summer Computer Science Institute (SCSI) at Carleton focuses on understanding how to think about these processes, how to program computers to implement them, and how to apply computer science ideas to real problems of interest. Students at SCSI will learn how to systematically approach problems like a computer scientist as they engage in classroom learning, hands-on lab activities, and collaborative guided research directed by Carleton faculty and mentored by undergraduate research assistants. The Summer Computer Science Institute will culminate with the SCSI Research Symposium where students will demonstrate the results of their collaborative guided research project. In short, during their three weeks at SCSI, students have a similar experience to what Carleton undergraduates who eventually major in Computer Science receive as they begin their academic journey. Current Sophomores and Juniors in High School are eligible to apply. We also have financial aid available for the program. View our website for all the details at http://go.carleton.edu/scsi.

description: Software Design 9, 10, 11, 12 Prerequisite: Computer Technologies or Department Approval Software Design is a one-semester course focused on writing computer software. The development of algorithms and good programming methodology will be learned through creating basic computer applications to game design. The goal of this course is to enable students to develop methods using the power of the computer to solve problems. Students will become familiar with programming methods such as top down design and object- oriented programming. They will learn to apply programming methods to writing program code and will become familiar with the structure and operation of Visual Basic. Advanced Software Design 9, 10, 11, 12 Prerequisite: Software Design Advanced Software Design is a one semester continuation of the study of programming begun in Software Design. The general course goals will continue to be addressed through the study of advanced programming topics. Students will develop algorithms to solve problems and will become increasingly familiar with programming methods such as top down design and procedure-oriented programming. They will apply programming methods to writing program codes and will become familiar with the structure and operation of the compiler used with Java. Some of the major topics covered in this course include: further works with structures from Software Design, procedures, scope of variables, arrays, sorting and searching routines, manipulation of data structures, string processing, working with files, graphics and advanced programming applications, Java applications and applets.

Languages covered this year include C++ and Python, and will expand to cover Java and Visual Basic next year. The final project for each class involves working as part of a software development team. We hope to integrate app development in the future as well. We use the UDK game engine and build characters in Blender and 3DS Max as part of a class game development team. Programming skills are used inside the game engine. Our web design class covers HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript, and other pertinent topics. We build a number of project websites as our skills progress over the course of the year, and hope to find a selection of non-profits for the students to build a site for as a capstone project. name: Gorzycki Middle School
description: In Video Game design students learn the basics of computer programming while exploring the tools and technology used to create various types of computer games including 2D, 3D, mobile, RPG, and even Kinect (body-controlled) games. We will experience the complex process of game creation from start to finish. No programming knowledge is required for the course; they learn as you go. In Video Game Design, students gain knowledge and skills in basic computer programming. Video Games are designed just like any other computer software; there is a set process that all software engineers go through. In this class we will explore this development process as well as the tools and technologies software engineers use to develop video games. In addition, we explore the art of video game design. What makes a game fun? How do you make a game challenging but not impossibly frustrating? What is it that makes a blockbuster game? During the first two six weeks, students will explore and learn several different game development platforms. The final six weeks, students will develop a prototype video game of their own design using the platform of their choosing following the software development process  starting at brainstorming and design all the way through testing.

They then work thorough a research and development phase to come up with an electronic project that engages a specific need which may be their own or someone elses. With the instructor as a guide, students access a plethora of example technology and online resources to learn and implement the necessary components of their idea. The course is about electronics, invention, being resourceful, innovation and working though the design process. By the end of this class each student should be able to look at a piece of Technology and at least understand the starting point to figuring out how to manipulate it if not make it into something unique. A student who repeats the course will be: asked to expand on the basic projects, held to higher standards, and expected to be a knowledge resource for peers.

name: J. Sargeant Reynolds Community College
description: CSC 130 Scientific Programming (3 cr.) Introduces a science and engineering-oriented, high-level programming language. Studies the C language and its application in problem solving in a structured programming environment. Includes the concepts and practice of structured programming, problem solving, top-down design of algorithms, basic C syntax, control structures, arrays, and data structures. Co-requisite or prerequisite: MTH 173 or equivalent. Pre-requisite: CSC 110 or permission of the instructor. Lecture 3 hours per week. CSC 155 Computer Concepts and Applications (3 cr.) Introduces basic hardware and software concepts of computer usage, programming languages, and the computer's impact on society. Includes applications of various types of software to illustrate how computers are used in sciences, social sciences, humanities, and education. Covers the use of an operating system, word processing, spreadsheets, e-mail, library access, database access and retrieval, presentation graphics, and the Internet. Lecture 3 hours per week. CSC 200 Introduction to Computer Science (3 cr.) Provides a broad introduction to computer science. Discusses architecture and the function of computer hardware, including networks and operating systems, data and instruction representation, and data organization. Covers software, algorithms, programming languages, and software engineering. Discusses artificial intelligence and theory of computation. Includes a hands-on component with oral and written presentations. Prerequisite: MTH 166 or equivalent with a grade of "C" or better. Lecture 3 hours per week. CSC 201 Computer Science I (4 cr.) Introduces algorithm and problem-solving methods. Emphasizes structured programming concepts, elementary data structures, and the study and use of a high-level programming language. Co-requisite: MTH 173 or equivalent or school approval. Lecture 4 hours per week. CSC 202 Computer Science II (4 cr.) Examines data structures, introduction to object-oriented design, and algorithm analysis. Covers data structures (including sets, strings, stacks, queues, arrays, records, files, linked lists, and trees), polymorphism, inheritance, exceptions, interfaces, abstract data types, algorithm analysis (including searching and sorting methods), and file structures. Prerequisite: CSC 201 with a grade of "C" or better. Co-requisite: MTH 174. Lecture 4 hours per week. CSC 205 Computer Organization (4 cr.) Examines the hierarchical structure of computer architecture. Focuses on multi-level machine organization. A simple assembler language is used by students to complete programming projects. Includes processors, instruction execution, addressing techniques, data representation, and digital logic. Prerequisite: CSC 202. Lecture 4 hours per week. CSC 210 Programming with C++ (4 cr.) Includes language syntax, problem-solving techniques, top-down refinement, procedure definition, loop invariance, theory of numerical errors, and debugging. Covers the syntax of the C++ language. Prerequisites: CSC 201, CSC 202, EGR 125, or instructor's approval. Co-requisite: MTH 173. Lecture 4 hours per week. CSC 295 Introduction to Discrete Structures (3 cr.) Covers Boolean algebra, combinatorial and sequential circuits, algorithms and algorithm analysis, recursion, recurrence relations, graphs, and trees. Prerequisites: CSC 201 and MTH 287 with a grade of C or better. Lecture 3 hours per week.

name: Urban Video Game Academy - DMV
description: 1. Background Urban Video Game Academy (UVGA) is a seven-year old project-based afterschool tech literacy and skills program design to promote STEM literacy and learning through the video game development process. UVGA and its board of advisors and program partners also help serve as a clearinghouse for the development of college and university scholarship opportunities through video game industry design competition events and their sponsor support. BLAXCOM Solutions, LLC manages and operates the UVGA as a for-profit program that provides an after-school technology solutions to the need for computer-based curriculums that utilizes the video game development process to engage and teach students for 21st century skills mastery. 2. Mission and Objectives The mission of the Urban Video Game Academy (UVGA) is to better prepare students in disadvantaged areas for post-secondary education and technology careers by teaching them the fundamentals of video game design and development. Our mission has three basic components: to expose dis-advantaged students to career opportunities in video game design and development, to educate them in how to create games, and to enhance their learning in math, science, reading, and writing, which are all important features of the video game development process. UVGA uses video game design and development to accomplish the following objectives: 1. To better prepare disadvantaged youth for college-level study in video game design and related fields such as computer science, digital art and engineering; 2. To enhance learning in math, science, reading, and writing through their applications in the video game development process; 3. To excite and inform disadvantaged youth about career alternatives in the video game design industry and related fields such as computer science, digital art and engineering; 4. To instill in disadvantaged youth a positive self image and teach them teamwork, leadership skills, and positive social interaction and communication skills; 5. To provide after-school and weekend classes that will keep disadvantaged youth engaged in productive activities; 6. To encourage related businesses and public organizations to support these efforts. The UVGA program reaches students from elementary to high school students in the Baltimore-DC area. The schools curriculum feature introductory graphic design software and computer programming, along with math enrichment. Most of the software utilize by the program can be obtained and installed with a no-fee-license. Software examples are: MS Power Point, MS Paint, ALICE 2.0, and Game Maker 8.1 Other software such as, Adobe Creative Suite 6 (CS6) which can include Photoshop, Illustrator, In-design, and FLASH). Other application curriculums include Scalextric4Schools (uses PTC Creo CAD) Autodesk Maya, 3D Max, Blender, and Zbrush for 3D modeling sculpting and animation rigging.

format_description: High School CS Into to Programming(VB), Intro to Java, AP Computer Science A
description: Introduction to Programming - Fall Semester Software has become an integral part of education and society over the past decade. From word processing to cell phone applications, the demand for programmers grows each and every day. This course serves as a platform for students to take an introductory look at how software is developed and to become familiar with a welcoming and user friendly coding language, Visual Basic. Students will explore the beginning aspects of how to read and write code, documentation, debugging, and working in teams to accomplish a common goal. The course culminates in a final project where students will use everything they learned over the course of the semesters to create an educational piece of software from scratch(Jeopardy, flashcards, etc.). No previous programming experience or computer skills required. Introduction to Java - Spring Semester The primary language in use today is Java, developed by Sun Microsystems. Java is the backbone of everything you see today, from applications to video games. In this course, we will study the beginning elements required to successfully understand and use Java. Students will be introduced to more conceptual elements such as object oriented programming, algorithm development, and class hierarchies. AP Computer Science A What is the most efficient way to sort a list of ten thousand names in the shortest amount of time? How can we continue to maintain a programs life span without excessive use of reusing code? These are the types of complicated yet intriguing questions that will be answered in AP Computer Science. This course takes students deep into the infrastructure of the Java language, including memory efficiency, searching and sorting, data structures, and polymorphism. There is also an in depth case study where students will have an opportunity to work with GridWorld, a simulated environment that mimics insect activity. In May, students will take the AP Exam.

name: The Software Entrepreneurs Club
description: We (the Software Entrepreneurs Club Mentors) work with a group of high school students, called the Software Entrepreneurs Club (the SEC), in Hillsboro, Oregon. We have recently published our first Windows 8 app to the Windows Store. Our app is a volunteer and donation management system, for use by schools and non-profits, worldwide. Our app, called Our Finest Hour (OFH), has been made possible by a handful of Microsoft employees who have had it within their respective powers to grant the SEC access to WP7 phones, Windows 8 (Samsung) tablets and design dollars (thru MAAP), software licenses and Azure hosting (thru BizSpark). In return for these donated hardware, software, and hosting resources, we have created (and published) our first Windows 8 OFH app and we are working on our first WP7 OFH app. Both apps are early prototypes, which will continually become more product worthy as we pursue our iterative software development methodology. Our Finest Hour is a multi-year project, which will soon start to produce recurring revenue for the SEC, to be used for further product development and club-sponsored college scholarships. We first started teaching mobile software development on WP7 smartphones in the high school classroom in 2011-2012, funded by a $20K grant from Intel. We had limited success in our development efforts, but we had enough success to encourage us to start an after-school software development club, called the SEC. We started the SEC this year as the 2nd phase of our experiment to see what a group of high school students can achieve when given: - technical leadership and mentoring - an after school program that is not bell-driven (when the bell rings, students leave the classroom) and is based upon each student's desire to achieve tasks, without receiving grades to measure their successes - donations of relevant hardware, software, and services - encouragement to design and create product worthy mobile software products, without formal software development schooling - the opportunity to compete for SEC sponsored college scholarships that are based largely on each student's contributions to SEC products We have a club roster of almost 50 students, with weekly team participation ranging from 19 to 27 students. High school students have a very active schedule these days, and we feel honored to have such a high weekly participation rate from our team members. In the next couple of years, we will be growing our team to encompass students from our other 3 high schools in the Hillsboro School District. We also plan to start working with high schools from other school districts across America, to help students at other schools to learn from our failures and successes. From a mentoring perspective, our main goal for the SEC is to help to produce local software development team members who come out of high school with a set of tools upon which they can build successful software development careers. Our team members are also being encouraged to continue to contribute to the SEC after they graduate from high school. In addition to software developers, we are working to also provide students with start-up experience in the disciplines of software quality assurance, product documentation, and software marketing and advertising. We are striving to teach our team members the importance of being able to work closely with each of the disciplines required to bring quality software products to market in a timely manner. We are excited about our results to date. We delivered our Windows 8 version of OFH within a very tight schedule dictated by Microsoft and we received very positive feedback from our sponsors at Microsoft about our deliverables to date. Links to OFH in the Windows Store, Our Finest Hour's Marketing Video, and Our Finest Hour's entry in Apps for Social Good (a Microsoft contest) are provided as follows: http://apps.microsoft.com/windows/app/ourfinesthour/e74a5998-c429-4652-9022-5aa459e0aecb http://vimeo.com/55793109 http://www.netsquared.org/project/our-finest-hour-software-entrepreneurs-club We hope you choose to install and use Our Finest Hour. We welcome you feedback on our app.

name: Institute of Data Processing Management of Nigeria
format_description: 6 months regular full time or part-time CS classes
description: INTRODUCING THE IDPM PROFESSIONAL PROGRAMME: A KNOWLEDGE AND SKILL UPGRADE STRATEGY FOR LOWER CADRE EMPLOYEES Introduction: The institute of Data Processing Management of Nigeria (IDPM) stands for Effective Data Processing and System Management. It is a professional body which is recognized under the companies and Allied Matters Decree 1, of 1990. It is the Nigerian counterpart of IDPM London, now known as the Institute for Management of Information System (IMIS) The IDPM (Institute of Data Processing Management of Nigeria) programme is designed to ease the process of knowledge and skill upgrades. It is particularly useful to employees with lower qualifications who wish to upgrade their knowledge and skill in order to move up the corporate ladder. The programme is self  paced, making it highly suitable to employees who cannot take study leaves. It could be run as part  time, full  time or any other schedule that suits the working condition of the employee. Completion of Part I&II and Part III&IV stages of the course is equivalent to OND (Ordinary National Diploma) and HND (Higher National Diploma) respectively; Graduates of the first stage (Part I&II) and second stage (Part III&IV) of the Professional programme are eligible for Direct Entry into 200 Level University Degree programmes and Post Graduate Degree programmes respectively if so wished. Courses that students can further in Direct Entry:  Accounting, Business Administration, Economics, Computer Economics, Computer Science, Computer Engineering, Business Education, etc Post Graduate Diploma (PGD):  Management Information System, Business Management, Public Administration, DP/Marketing Management, DP/Management Accounting, Information Technology, etc Universities where IDPM Certificates are recognised  Olabisi Onabanjo University, Ambrose Alli University, Ekiti State University, Crescent University, Obafemi Awolowo University, Ladoke Akintola University, St. Clement University; Australia, University of Applied Science; Port-Novo, European-America University; New York, (Ghana Campus & Nigeria Satellite ) Walden University, London Sikkim Manipal University; India (Ghana Campus) etc. Professional Bodies around the world where IDPM Certificates are recognised Association for Computer Machinery (ACM); New York USA, Institute of Management Information System (IMIS); London, Institute of Engineering and Technology (IET); United Kingdom, The Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE); USA, Nigeria Institute of Management (NIM); Nigeria, Chartered Institute of Commerce (CIC); Nigeria, Chartered Institute of Certified Secretaries and Reporters (CICSR), Nigeria. etc NB: We have only listed Universities in which Graduates of the programme are currently offering courses; you are encouraged to make enquiries into other Universities not listed independently. Requirements: Intending students are required to have Five (5) O  Level Credits, although students still awaiting their results may be considered. More than a Course At IDPM we take our students through rigorous Quantitative, Verbal and Analytical training to make them better equipped to face the challenges of the modern world. We prepare them not only for the Labour market but also to become worthy entrepreneurs through our management courses. Finally, we make them well rounded by applying hands  on computer techniques to problem solving and financial management. Our Training Staff With our army of Graduates from reputable universities, members of world class professional institutes and holders of international certifications; our students are in great hands. For more details contact: Snr. Analyst Adebayo Sulaiman AIDPM Lagos State Coordinator, National Database Manager 08122769953, 08035188256 www.idpmng.org; info@idpmng.org

name: Loveless Academic Magnetic Program (LAMP) High School
description: The Loveless Academic Magnet Program (LAMP) provides highly motivated students with the opportunity to develop knowledge, creativity, and academic skills through participation in advanced studies in English, mathematics, science, social studies, foreign languages, computer science, and a wide array of interest electives. The stringent college preparatory curriculum prepares students who are interested in pursuing careers in medicine, applied science, government and similar areas of distinction for admission to the most prestigious college programs in the nation. The Loveless curriculum, which includes 16 Advanced Placement courses and a variety of academic competitive teams, provides students with the opportunity to gain superior educational preparation through intensified classroom and community experiences. A sports program, under the guidance of the Alabama High School Athletic Association, is based upon student interest. Acceptance into Loveless is based upon academic records indicating demonstrated ability to complete higher-level academic courses, maintain disciplined study and work habits, and acceptable conduct and attendance. Ninth-grade applicants should have completed Intro Algebra (Algebra 1 preferred). Tenth-grade applicants should have completed Algebra 1 (Geometry preferred). Upon review of the student's academic records and completion of a personal interview, candidates are selected for enrollment based upon space availability. Students must maintain, for the current school year, a weighted academic average of 2.5 or better in the academic core courses (English, history, math, science and foreign languages) and acceptable conduct and attendance records.

name: Norfolk Academy
description: When: All day for 5 days starting Monday, June 17th. Ages: Entering 6th - 9th grade From the course description: Computers are everywhere, and sometimes it can seem unbelievable that they can do what they do. They can understand words, display pictures and video, and even make sounds. Most people know that someone, somewhere, programmed each computer to do what it does, but the computer code behind these programs can seem strange and even intimidating at first. This course will dive into computers to explore the way they work and the code that runs them, using the small, inexpensive Raspberry Pi computer. Well learn just how text gets into the computer, how people have used text to tell computers what to do (i.e. what programming languages are), learn the basics of the Python programming language, and finally read and modify the code behind a few fun games written in Python. Students will learn how to understand technology by breaking it down into accessible pieces. In the process, theyll discover the fun of using computer code as an outlet for their creativity. A Raspberry Pi computer, activity kit, and extra projects are included, so students can continue learning and creating afterwards, and a growing number of online educational resources for the Pi are available as well. The only prerequisites for this course are curiosity, creativity and drive!

name: University of Twente, Faculty of Behavioural Sciences
description: Why should a psychologist (student) ever learn programming? There are quite a few reasons why you should: You want to write your bachelor thesis in experimental psychology? - Program your own experimental designs. You are interested in media psychology, e-learning or human-computer interaction? - Program your own interactive prototypes of websites, multimedia apps asf. You are dealing with statistical analysis on complex data sets? - Do powerful data analysis beyond what SPSS offers. You are a creative person and like arts? - Express your ideas by own pieces of interactive art. You are a technophile person and love computers? - Make the most out of it by writing your own programs. The course introduces programming to third year Psychology students. The course aims at a gentle, illustrative and non-intimidating introduction to common programming concepts. The course introduces the programming language Processing, a simplified Java, targeted at artists and designers. Besides its Java heritage, Processing has the advantage of being graphical. Students can produce nice looking drawings and animations with ease, instead of being bound to the command line. After about 6 weeks, students have acquired basic programming skills, up to developing small interactive programs and writing object-oriented code. For the remaining two weeks students choose one of three workshops, which focus on one particular purpose for programming within Psychology: (1) programming psychological experiments, (2) scientific programming and (3) programming interactive media.

format_description: Intro to CS Programing and Repair
description: The Columbus School for Girls One Laptop Per Child Service Learning Project engages high school girls in service through computer science. What started out as a service trip has expanded to many different student-driven projects that use computer science as a vehicle to improve the world. Students learn Etoys, repair and refurbish XO laptops, and prepare to teach Etoys to elementary school students. The service aspect of this course engages girls with technology in a deeply meaningful way. The service becomes the objective rather than the computer programming or the hardware and software troubleshooting. A secondary gain, but a primary goal, is that students are being introduced to Computer Science in a way that is attractive, engaging, and meaningful. The numbers of women in computer science have plummeted in the past decade, and remain low, so recruiting and retaining women into CS is an urgent need. This project helps to address the initial recruiting aspect of the "pipeline problem" by embedding the computer science into the goal of teaching and service. The science becomes something students learn along the way.

description: Web Design 1 This course is an introduction to creating professional-quality websites for business, community, entertainment, or personal uses. Students will develop the knowledge and skills to create attractive and functional websites, emphasizing both the technology and design processes. They will learn the fundamental concepts and tools for creating websites using HTML (the language used to structure web pages and online content) and CSS (the language used to give a website its form and visual style). Students will develop a final project of their own choosing, using a high-level Content Management System (CMS) such as WordPress to create a fully functional website. uses. Web Design 2 This course is a continuation of Web Design 1, for students who wish to pursue the field in greater depth. Students in this course will conceive, research, design, develop, and operate a functioning website for a real client or user community. The website focus and goals, chosen by the student, are first developed in a project proposal. Once the project is approved, students are expected to work with a high degree of independence and self-direction to bring it to fruition, emphasizing good planning, documentation, communication, design, technology, and usability. Team projects are encouraged, as web design is a highly collaborative and multidisciplinary endeavor. Introduction to Computer Science 1 This course is an introduction to computer science and software engineering for all students interested in developing software applications, not just using them. Through a project-oriented approach, students will explore a variety of programming systems and languages to create interactive applications and systems. By collaborating in a hands-on environment, students will learn problem solving, software design, debugging strategies, and the foundations of computer science (data structures, procedures, and algorithms). Students will work on projects (both individual and team) in the areas of graphics and games, animation and art, electronics systems, and interactive fashion, all using open-source software tools such as Scratch, Arduino, and Processing. AP Computer Science This course is an introductory study of the theory and practice of computer science and software engineering. It covers fundamental concepts of programming, including data structures, algorithms, and procedures, as well as object-oriented methodologies. Students will learn problem-solving techniques, software design and documentation skills, and development and debugging strategies, all using the Java programming language. This Advanced Placement course is the equivalent of a first-year college course in computer science, and is based on the University of Washingtons curriculum for its introductory computer science course (CSE 142/143). It prepares students to take the Advanced Placement Computer Science A Exam in the spring. It is also offered for University of Washington credit as part of the UW in the High School program. Computer Science Projects 1/2 This course provides an opportunity for students with significant programming experience to work on a semester-long project of their own choosing. Students will learn structured software engineering processes and project management strategies, as well as explore advanced topics in computer science. Under the supervision of the instructor and local computing professionals and working in teams, they will develop project proposals, implement their designs, and document and present their work. Students taking this course are expected to be self-motivated and capable of independent, supported work. Students who wish to spend an additional semester in this pursuit may register for CS Projects 2 also.

name: Heritage High School
description: Computer Programming - Computer Programming is designed to focus on problem-solving skills, critical thinking, and computer ethics. Students learn to design (structured) algorithms to solve (programming) problems using Visual Basic. The coverage of algorithms and design techniques is general enough to enable the student to use this course as a foundation for structured program solving in any language. Programming is taught through lectures, demonstration, analysis, and programming projects generally related to math, science, and business. AP-Computer Science - This is considered a college level introductory course in computer science using JAVA as the programming language. A large part of the course is built around the development of computer programs or parts of programs that correctly solve a given problem. The course also emphasizes the design issues that make programs understandable, adaptable, and, when appropriate, reusable. At the same time, the development of useful computer programs and program modules is used as a context for introducing other important concepts in computer science, including the development and analysis of algorithms, the development and use of fundamental data structures, and the study of standard algorithms and typical applications.

description: Exploring Computer Science A & B: Are you wondering where you fit in in the world of technology? Then Exploring Computer Science (ECS) is the class for you! description: Introduction to Computer Programming/Game Design 1: This course is a one-trimester elective course that introduces students to the field of computer science and game design using the Visual Basic (VB) programming language. Students will apply these constructs to game theory and game design. (Note: Game Design 2, 3, and 4 are under development and will be offered in 2013 and 2014)

name: Granada High School
description: Computer Science and Software Engineering: This course is a Project Lead the Way pilot course (http://www.pltw.org/) emphasizing the power of computational thinking and analytical inquiry. The 4 units of study are 1) Graphics and Computer Science which covers concepts such as iteration, objects, classes, events, and code efficiency. 2) Web Design and Information Technology including code writing, networking concepts, privacy, and security. 3) Information Science which introduces discrete mathematics, probability and association, and data visualization. 4) Software Engineering where students predict solutions and develop strategies for handling large projects.

name: Granada High School
description: Advanced Placement (AP) Computer Science: This two trimester course expands on programming basics that students learned in one of the prerequisite courses. We delve deep into programming concepts and computer science, and use the Java language to develop and analyze algorithms, develop and use data structures, recognize and adapt standard algorithms and typical applications, and understand basic hardware and software components of computer systems. Students learn object-oriented programming by studying a large, game-based program and prepare for the Computer Science Advanced Placement test.

name: Centennial High School
description: Videp Game Design This yearlong course teaches students the knowledge, skills, and abilities necessary to create games in the C# programming language using the Microsoft XNA Framework. Games are created in the Microsoft Windows Environment using the Microsoft XNA framework which includes Microsoft Visual Studio 2008 and all games created will be played on the XBOX 360. Objectives of the course include but are not limited to understanding the principles of testdriven game development, using state machines when creating a program and how program states are expressed on a state diagram, comprehending software engineering terms such as coupling, cohesion, and encapsulation, and comprehending the reasons behind code re factoring. During the course of the first semester students will test and earn their Microsoft Technology Associate  Software Development Fundamentals Certificate. Finally, by the conclusion of the course, students will develop, create, and test their own game from start to finish. Intermediate Video Game Design This yearlong course teaches students intermediate knowledge, skills, and abilities necessary to create games in the C# programming language using the Microsoft XNA Framework 4.0, and also includes an introduction to 3D gaming using the Unity 3D development engine. In this project-based learning course, games created in the Microsoft Windows Environment using Microsoft Visual Studio 2010 and Unity 3D are designed to be played on the XBOX 360. Objectives of the course include but are not limited to objects, properties of objects, programming structure, decision and data structures, iteration, looping, recursion, arrays, simple text file input, and more complex functions. During the course of the year students will test and earn their Microsoft Technology Associate  Software Development Fundamentals and/or Microsoft Technology Associate  Gaming Development Fundamentals Certificate. At the end of the year, students will create their own 3D game world using Unity 3D. Topics include learning the interface, Asset Workflow, Creating Scenes, and Publishing on various platforms including iOS, Android, Xbox360, and Windows Mobile. Finally during the course of the school year, students will create, publish and play their own gaming project. This course is recommended for students who would like to pursue a advanced degree in video game design, or work in the video gaming industry. Java Programming The purpose of this course is to expose the student to the various principles of the object-orientated computer programming language of Java. It will train each student in programming methodology in order to produce exceptional computer-based solutions to real-world problems. The course is based on the standard Java library classes from the AP Java subset; in addition, it provides an in-depth study of programming methodology, algorithms, data structures, and polymorphism. Finally, by taking this course students will enhance their critical thinking skills. Upon completion of this course, the student will be able to do the following:  Write and debug programs in the Java programming language  Understand and use object-orientated programming techniques and data structures to solve complex problems.  Analyze a problem, develop a flowchart programming plan, implement the plan, and revise the plan to produce a high level-programming product.  Use a top-down approach to programming using a high-level computing language, Java.  Create program documents  Seamlessly adapt to other similar programming languages offered at the college level.

name: Oakland Technical High School
description: The Computer Science and Technology Academy at Oakland Technical High School is for students who enjoy using computers and want to learn more about them. Students begin by enrolling in Exploring Computer Science in 10th grade Students begin by enrolling in Exploring Computer Science in 10th grade, a course specifically designed for socially diverse group of students and introduce the students to the breadth of the field of computer science. The computer academy program will develop in students the computational thinking practices of algorithm development, study of computer principles, their hardware and software designs, their applications, and their impact on society. At the end of 10th grade, students will be sufficiently well-rounded to continuing learning more about programming, database design, web development, and networking. Students who complete all three years of the program will have at least three different options. First, those who choose to work immediately after high school gradation will have sufficient academic and practical skills to get an entry level computer related job. Next, we are coordinating a program with Peralta Colleges, so that students can continue their studies at Alameda or any of the Peralta Colleges, preparing them for more technical and higher paying jobs. Lastly, for those students who plan to pursue a career in computer science or engineering, or any other position that requires a four year university degree, we offer a balanced preparation that ensures the students will complete all necessary requirements through articulation. The Courses taught include: Exploring Computer Science is designed to introduce students to the breadth of the field of computer science. The goal of Exploring Computer Science is to develop in students the computational thinking practices of algorithm development, problem solving and programming within the context of problems that are relevant to the lives of todays students. Students will also be introduced to topics such as interface design, limits of computers and societal and ethical issues of software engineering. Computer programming 1 The Computer Programming 1 course covers the fundamentals of database design and programming using oracle object relational database management system as part of the second year computer academy curriculum. In the second semester they begin the CS principles course where they take on the 9 big CS ideas as outlined in the College Boards principles course. Computer Programming 2 / APCSA This course builds on the strong foundation of structured programming which the students have built over the years to train them on the concepts of object-oriented programming using the JAVA programming language. They will build their own classes as well as use ready-made classes to simplify work with strings, arraylist, stacks, and queues.

description: The school has two after school clubs available that work on programming skills. Both clubs have a focus on creative learning, computational thinking and integrating and creating software based on non-traditional interfaces for video games. In the Junior Video Game Design Club (Grade 4 and 5) students work on building the basics of computational learning. This club uses Scratch and Gamestar Mechanic. For the 2012/2013 school year, Junior Club meets on Wednesdays from 3:00 - 4:00. The Senior Video Game Design Club (Grade 6-8) has a beginners component that also begins with programming through Scratch. The plan is that students can be matched with mentors in order to support learning any language that they are interested, once they have a basic understanding of the programming processes. Currently we have students working on learning how to use Scratch, Alice 3D, as well as setting up and maintaining a school Minecraft.edu server. Our 2013 projects include using LEGO WeDO sensors and motors, Makey Makey, the Microsoft Kinect and Scratch to create interactive programs and games that are not dependent on keystrokes or the mouse in order to work. description: Introduction to Microsoft Visual BASIC programming language, an object-oriented language for building Windows-based applications. This overview helped to under why and how many computer commands interact with their host hardware platform.

name: IMACS - Institute for Mathematics and Computer Science (at Rashkis Elementary)
description: Computer Programming and Virtual Robotics - (a) Computer Programming: Students learn to write computer programs with LOGO, a graphic-based computer programming language developed at MIT. With individualized guidance, students are challenged by projects designed by the IMACS Curriculum Development Group. (This class also serves as the ideal introduction to the more advanced university-level Computer Science class.) (b) Virtual Robotics: Students use a toolbox of wheels, gears and sensors to design, build and program robots. The robots themselves operate in a virtual world that mirrors the physical world, complete with friction and laws governing conservation of momentum and energy. Students learn to succeed in this course by analyzing and working through the challenging problems they encounter. University Computer Science - The IMACS Computer Science program is second to none in its ability to engage talented secondary school students with challenging, university-level curriculum that focuses on computational thinking and go well beyond just coding. Students who complete this sequence of classes develop a deep understanding of core concepts while becoming fluent in three programming languages (Scheme, Haskell, and Python). The IMACS approach provides students with a unique academic advantage in college and beyond.

name: Sir John A. Macdonald Secondary School
description: Introduction to Computer Studies, Open (ICS2O): This course introduces students to computer programming. Students will plan and write simple computer programs by applying fundamental programming concepts, and learn to create clear and maintainable internal documentation. They will also learn to manage a computer by studying hardware configurations, software selection, operating system functions, networking, and safe computing practices. Students will also investigate the social impact of computer technologies, and develop an understanding of environmental and ethical issues related to the use of computers. Introduction to Computer Science, University Level (ICS3U): This course introduces students to computer science. Students will design software independently and as part of a team, using industry-standard programming tools and applying the software development life-cycle model. They will also write and use subprograms within computer programs. Students will develop creative solutions for various types of problems as their understanding of the computing environment grows. They will also explore environmental and ergonomic issues, emerging research in computer science, and global career trends in computer-related fields. Introduction to Computer Programming, College Level (ICS3C): This course introduces students to computer programming concepts and practices. Students will write and test computer programs, using various problem-solving strategies. They will learn the fundamentals of program design and apply a software development life-cycle model to a software development project. Students will also learn about computer environments and systems, and explore environmental issues related to computers, safe computing practices, emerging technologies, and postsecondary opportunities in computer-related fields. Web Desgin, Open (IDC3O): In this course, you will learn how to design and create interactive websites that include text, graphic images, commerce, and multimedia components such as audio, video, Flash, and shopping carts. You will create pages using HTML, Javascript, CSS, and use available code editors such as Adobe Dreamweaver and image editors such as Adobe Photoshop and Adobe Fireworks. Computer Science, University Level (ICS4U): This course enables students to further develop knowledge and skills in computer science. Students will use modular design principles to create complex and fully documented programs, according to industry standards. Student teams will manage a large software development project, from planning through to project review. Students will also analyse algorithms for effectiveness. They will investigate ethical issues in computing and further explore environmental issues, emerging technologies, areas of research in computer science, and careers in the field. Computer Programming, College Level (ICS4C): This course further develops students computer programming skills. Students will learn object-oriented programming concepts, create object-oriented software solutions, and design graphical user interfaces. Student teams will plan and carry out a software development project using industry-standard programming tools and proper project management techniques. Students will also investigate ethical issues in computing and expand their understanding of environmental issues, emerging technologies, and computer-related careers.

name: Phillips Academy
description: We offer 6 courses - 1 yearlong course (AP) and 5 trimester-long: * Intro to computer science ( teaches Scratch, Python, VPython programming); * Intro to computer science - website design (teaches HTML, CSS, Javascript); * Intro to discrete mathematics and programming (hybrid course, teaches Python); * AP computer science - prepares for the College Board AP exam (teaches Java, yearlong, no CS prereqs); * Data structures (Java, post-AP, 4-hours per week) * Advanced website design - Rails version (teaches Ruby, Rails platform, SQL, 4-hours per week) * After-school club for students who want to do more (contests, App Inventor for Android, Finch robots)
languages: HTML | Java | Javascript | Python | Ruby | Scratch

name: Milwaukee School of Engineering
description: MSOE offers ABET accredited degrees in Software Engineering and Computer Engineering. Course descriptions for in major courses in the freshman year are included below. SE-1011: Software Development I  This course provides an introduction to object-oriented software development using the Java programming language. Emphasis is placed on translating written problem descriptions into robust software solutions. Topics covered include Java program structure, algorithmic problem solving and modularization, I/O statements, control constructs, looping techniques, class libraries, user defined classes and methods, arrays, and ArrayLists. Course website: http://msoe.us/taylor/se1011 SE-1021: Software Development II  This course continues the study of objected oriented software development using the Java programming language. Students design, document and implement software classes and incorporate these classes into larger software applications. Topics covered include abstraction, encapsulation, declaring and implementing abstract data types, interfaces, inheritance, polymorphism, and simple event-driven programming. Course Website: http://msoe.us/taylor/se1021 CS-2852: Data Structures  This course covers the organization of data and the algorithms that act upon them. The topics of arrays, linked lists, stacks, queues, trees, sets, and hash tables are introduced. Fundamentals of algorithm performance are also introduced, with an emphasis placed on time complexity analysis. Laboratory activities include implementation of data structures as well as the application of data structures from standard libraries. Course Website: http://msoe.us/taylor/cs2852 CE-1900: Digital Logic I  This course introduces combinational logic analysis and design. The topics include digital signals, binary numbers, logic gates, logic families, combinational building blocks, Boolean algebra, combinational circuit analysis, and combinational circuit design techniques. Emphasis is placed on the VHDL hardware description language as a vehicle for circuit description and simulation. Laboratory exercises allow the student to design, implement, and test a wide range of digital circuits using standard logic families and programmable logic devices. Course Website: https://faculty-web.msoe.edu/meier/ce1900/ CE-1910: Digital Logic II  This course introduces sequential logic analysis and design. Sequential systems create outputs that depend on the current system inputs as well as a history of past inputs. Thus, these systems exhibit memory behavior. The topics include flip-flops, registers, counters, shift-registers, algorithmic state machines, and memories. Emphasis is placed on the VHDL hardware description language as a vehicle for circuit description and simulation. Laboratory exercises allow the student to design, implement, and test a wide range of digital circuits using standard logic families and programmable logic devices. Course Website: https://faculty-web.msoe.edu/meier/ce1910/

name: Roswell High School
description: http://fultonschools.org/teacher/lee/ Course Information: Mr. Lee teaches four courses at this time. Please read the course descriptions below. Computer Applications Course #07.4411000 Knowing how to use computer applications software is a basic skill for everyone. Students in this course become proficient in word processing, database, spreadsheet, publishing, and presentation software. Essentially, we will be studying the Microsoft Office Suite which includes MS Word, Access, Excel, and Powerpoint software. Given time, we will also explore Publisher and some web page development. This course is recommended for any student interested in taking further computing classes. Computer Applications Syllabus Computing in the Modern World Course #11.4130000 (be careful not to confuse course number with Fundamentals of Web Site Design below) The goal of this course is to provide all students with an introduction to the principles of computer science and its place in the modern world. This course should also help students to use computers effectively in their lives, thus providing a foundation for successfully integrating their own interests and careers with the resources of a technological society. Topics include hardware maintenance and design, networking, web page development, and programming. Computer Applications is highly recommended before taking this class. Computing in the Modern World Syllabus Fundamentals of Web Site Design & Development Course #11.4310000 (be careful not to confuse course number with Computing in the Modern World above) Students in this course learn how to design web sites. Included are site planning, page layout, graphic design, and the use of markup languages. Forms and scripts are used to add interactivity and database access to web sites. Additionally, the student will explore the use of leading edge software including Adobe PhotoShop, Dreamweaver, and Flash. Computer Applications is highly recommended before taking this class. Fundamentals of Web Site Design Syllabus AP Computer Science A with Java Course #11.2160010 The AP Computer Science A course is designed to provide students with a learning experience equivalent to that of an introductory college course in Computer Science. The AP Computer Science A course emphasizes object-oriented programming methodology with a concentration on problem solving and algorithm development, and includes the study of data structures, design, and abstraction. Other topics covered include an overview of the history of computing, basics of computing systems, ethics in computing, syntax/semantics in JAVA, subroutines, selection, repetition, classes and their methods, and an introduction to the GridWorld Case Study. This course follows the AP course description written by The College Board. This is a two-semester course that will culminate in the Advanced Placement Examination in Computer Science A. At present, the programming language utilized for the AP Computer Science A course is Java. A grade of B or higher in Algebra 2 is the prerequisite for this particular course of study. Students interested in taking AP Computer Science should have all of the following; o Prior experience with the rigors of an AP course load. o A PSAT Math score of 600 or higher. o Taken Computer Applications or have a high degree of familiarity with computers o A good work ethic. AP Computer Science A with Java Syllabus

name: Storming Robots

description: Utilize Robotics to teach programming structure. For Gr.3 to 6: Use Robolab and Heavily focus on flowchart design. For Gr. 7 to 12: a) Start them with RobotC; b) For those who meet the minimum requirement, they will learn C/C++ programming focusing on analysis and algorithms, not just learning the language. Heavily project-based. We find application based approach is the best way to instill programming and analysis skill. Some of our students engage in Artificial Intelligence algorithm such as Sieve Prime number generator, N-Queen Problem, Huffman Encoding, Depth First Search Recursion, Flood Fill Algorithm, etc. c) For the most advanced students, we teach Arduino - Sketch C programming. Again, it is 100% application/project based. Our model has proven itself successful via our students' accomplishment in various levels of robotics competitions which require vigorous software programming and computational skills. We do not employ conventional teaching and grading method. Students do not get promoted to the next level until they demonstrate mastery of the current level. Students' levels are not guaged by tests and home work assignment, but via their accomplishment of projects which embody the iterative software development cycle.

description: Students in the Integrated Information Technology program at the University of South Carolina receive an in-depth background in information technologies in five major areas: computer networking, database systems, corporate training and development, web development, and project management. In the computer networking area, students learn about networking theory, hardware, configuration, design, installation, and network operating system administration. In the database systems area, students learn to create and maintain databases through courses in Access, Visual Basic, and Oracle SQL. The training area covers corporate training and training systems development. In web development, students learn to create web sites using HTML and Javascript as well as content management systems such as Joomla and Drupal. Students get extensive coursework and experience in information systems project management. Students may take electives in specialized IT areas such as mainframe computing, information security management, and hospitality technology. To maximize the learning experience, all IIT students must complete an internship and a capstone course that incorporates all the major IT subject areas.

description: CS 102 - Introduction to Computer Animation 5.0 Credits Introduces some basic techniques and tools of computer animation and sound production. Students develop their own unique computer character sprites, and create a short interactive computer animation with accompanying sound and music CS 115 - Introduction to Programming 5.0 Credits An introductory course in programming using VB.NET. No previous programming experience is expected. Topics include designing, creating and debugging interactive, event-driven programs with a graphical user interface and developing problem-solving skills CS& 131 - Computer Science I C++ 5.0 Credits Introduction to programming for students majoring in Computer Science, technical or engineering fields. Covers the fundamental syntax and constructs of the C/C++ programming languages and general concepts of programming CS 132 - Computer Science II C++ 5.0 Credits Intermediate concepts of object-oriented program design and implementation using the C++ language. Topics include class design, polymorphism, composition, common algorithms, and the general use of object-oriented programming principles and algorithms for sorts and searches CS 133 - Computer Science III C++ 5.0 Credits C++ Data Structures. Topics include: data structures such as list, stacks, queues, various binary trees and iterators; single, multiple and virtual inheritance, polymorphism, the STL and object- oriented design techniques CS 135 - C and C++ Review I 5.0 Credits Part 1 of a two-quarter sequence. A review of the fundamental concepts of the C and C++ languages. Topics include program flow constructs, functions, references and pointers, operator overloading, file I/O, classes, and object oriented design CS 136 - C and C++ Review II 5.0 Credits Part II of a two-quarter sequence. Basic characteristics of C/C++ and the use of C++ for Windows graphics and game programming. Advanced features of C++ such as Template Library, exception handling, bit operations, and the use of C++ to implement 2D graphics techniques CS& 141 - Computer Science I Java 5.0 Credits Introduction to Java programming. Topics include basic Java syntax, data types, control structures, methods, object representation using classes, graphics, Applets and arrays, all within a framework of general object oriented programming principles CS 142 - Computer Science II Java 5.0 Credits Intermediate Java programming. Topics include algorithm development, searching/sorting, complexity/efficiency, recursion, user interface design, class relationships including composition and inheritance and an introduction to abstract data types CS 143 - Computer Science III Java 5.0 Credits Java Data Structures. Topics include data structures such as lists, stacks, queues and various binary trees, inheritance and interfaces, using standard collection classes and algorithms and Generics CS 161 - Introduction to Computer Game Development 5.0 Credits Fundamentals of computer game programming, including a survey of computer game categories and platforms, major game components, an overview of the game development process, and an introduction to game graphics programming using the Windows API CS 162 - Graphics and Game Programming I 5.0 Credits Introduction to the Microsoft DirectX game and graphics libraries and their use in the development of Windows based games, animation, and other graphics applications CS 163 - Graphics and Game Programming II 5.0 Credits Fundamental concepts used in 2D graphics and animation, as well as the techniques and tools needed to create a game application using the DirectX 2D graphics and animation library CS 185 - Two-Dimensional Game Development Project 5.0 Credits Techniques and tools used to create non-graphic game components such as joystick I/O, sound, video, networking, and artificial intelligence. Students integrate these components into a 2D game project CS 215 - Intermediate Visual Basic.NET 5.0 Credits Intermediate topics of visual program design and implementation using Visual Basic.NET. Topics include arrays, object-oriented programming, files and streams, error handling and debugging SQL, database programming with ADO.NET, and multimedia CS 216 - Advanced Visual Basic.NET Programming 5.0 Credits Introduces advanced topics of visual program design and implementation using Visual Basic.NET. Topics include database programming and SQL, ADO.NET, data structures and collections, ASP.NET and Web services, and networking CS 217 - Internet Programming with .NET 5.0 Credits Design, implementation and deployment of applications, web services, and components in an enterprise environment. Uses the latest tools and languages supported by the .NET framework CS 218 - Introduction to C# 5.0 Credits Introduces the C# programming language. Topics include basic C# syntax, data types, control structures, methods, object representation using classes and arrays, all within a framework of general object-oriented programming principles CS 225 - UNIX Shell Programming 5.0 Credits An intermediate course that extends previous experience with the Bourne/bash shells to program scripts used to automate system administrative tasks. Topics include environment/user defined variables, branches, loops, menus, user interaction, and functions CS 226 - Advanced UNIX: Perl 5.0 Credits Introduction to the Perl language and its use in UNIX scripting. Topics include scalar, list, hash and reference variables, control structures, formats, regular expressions, file and process input/ output, subroutines, Object-Oriented Perl, and Perls relationship to other languages CS 271 - Three-Dimensional Game Development I DirectX 5.0 Credits First of a three-course sequence. Introduction to 3D game programming using the latest version of the Microsoft 3D API. Topics include a review of 3D mathematics, transformation pipeline, initializing Direct 3D, vertex and index buffers, and single and multi-texture effects CS 272 - Three-Dimensional Game Development II DirectX 5.0 Credits Second of a three-course sequence covering 3D game programming using the latest version of the Microsoft 3D API. Topics include camera management systems, texture compression, advanced texturing and alpha blending, loading GILES levels, and advanced 3D rendering techniques CS 273 - Three-Dimensional Game Development III DirectX 5.0 Credits Third of a three-course sequence covering 3D game programming using the latest version of the Microsoft 3D API. Topics include D3DX meshes, progressive meshes, hierarchies, and frame based and mesh hierarchy based animation CS 274 - Three-Dimensional Game Development IV DirectX 5.0 Credits Course covers 3D game programming using the latest version of the DirectX API. Topics include particle systems, shadows, reflections, curved surface representations, collision detection and spatial partitioning CS 283 - Artificial Intelligence for Game Developers 5.0 Credits Data structures and algorithms used in computer game AI. Includes a discussion of the two most general aspects of game AI including pathfinding and decision making. Pathfinding topics include grid traversal and search algorithms, pathfinding with A*, and waypoint networks. Decision making topics include finite state machines, scripting, and squad level AI CS 285 - Three-Dimensional Game Development Project 5.0 Credits Application of basic 3D game concepts, techniques, and tools to the design and creation of a 3D game
