name: Marquette University
description: COSC 1010. Introduction to Computer Programming. 4 cr. hrs. Introduction to abstraction, algorithmic thinking, simulation and testing for computer-based problem solving. Students will learn a high-level programming language and use tools developed by computer scientists and software engineers to solve problems. No prior programming experience is assumed. 3 hrs. lecture, 2 hrs. lab. Two years of college preparatory mathematics required. COSC 1020. Object-Oriented Software Design. 4 cr. hrs. Software development using Java. Topics include classes and interfaces as design patterns, the Java API, current object-oriented design methodologies, an introduction to the Internet and the development of Web applications. Projects involve the development of graphical interfaces and net-centric applications. 3 hrs. lecture, 2 hrs. lab. Prereq: COSC 1010 or advanced placement. COSC 3250. Operating Systems. 3 cr. hrs. Fundamental concepts of operating systems including process control and scheduling, synchronization, memory management, file systems, device control, and the boot process. Includes module on C programming language. Course may consist of a 3 hr. lecture or a 2 hr. lecture and 2 hr. lab. Prereq: COSC 2200 and COSC 2100 or COSC 2010. COSC 3410. Programming Languages. 3 cr. hrs. A comparative study of programming paradigms and representative programming languages. Topics include binding times, control of data, control of execution, execution environment, the role of language as an organizational tool, modularization, and the concept and significance of universal programming languages. Includes module on Scheme programming language. Prereq: COSC 2100 or COSC 2010. COSC 3977. Problem Solving -- Programming. 1 cr. hr. Students will study and implement computing problems, examine their solutions, apply classical algorithms, and formulate strategies for teamwork and problem solving in a programming contest environment. This course is a preparation for the ACM International Collegiate Programming Contest. S/U grade assessment. Prereq: Cons. of instr.

description: The AP Computer Science A course is an introductory course in computer science. Because the design and implementation of computer programs to solve problems involve skills that are fundamental to the study of computer science, a large part of the course is built around the development of computer programs that correctly solve a given problem. These programs should be understandable, adaptable, and, when appropriate, reusable. At the same time, the design and implementation of computer programs is used as a context for introducing other important aspects of computer science, including the development and analysis of algorithms, the development and use of fundamental data structures, the study of standard algorithms and typical applications, and the use of logic and formal methods. In addition, the responsible use of these systems is an integral part of the course.

name: Santa Fe High School
description: Computer Science for All is a computational science course open to high school students. This semester long course uses computer modeling as an introduction to computer science and computational thinking while exposing students to the breadth of applicability of computer science to solving real-world problems. Computer programming exercises and activities in an agent-based modeling environment (NetLogo) lead up to building a computational science project that meets the criteria set by the Supercomputing Challenge. Students will become familiar with the iterative design, build, and test development cycle common to computer science and engineering, and learn computer science constructs, processes and tools while creating models of local phenomena as complex systems. Students will also learn mathematics for modeling, probability and statistics, and data analysis techniques

name: Waukesha County Technical College
description: 152-107 Intro to Programming Learn fundamental object-oriented programming (OOP) concepts: classes, objects, methods, properties, event handling, control logic, data structures, algorithms, concurrency and problem solving, with minimal exposure to language semantics. A unique drag-and-drop, graphical environment is provided, which results in mistake-free code generation. Hone problem-solving skills while exploring concepts visually, and then see how these concepts translate to code. This is a common, required course for programmer analysts, network specialists and computer support specialists. Degree-tailored language semantics will be introduced in the final weeks of the course. 152-134 Java Programming Get a rigorous introduction to the Java J2SE programming language and object-oriented (OOP) programming concepts such as class responsibilities, composition, inheritance, interfaces, encapsulation and polymorphism. Design and build java desktop applications and applets using Sun Microsystems J2SE Java Development Kit and popular Integrated Development Environments. Explore the Java API (standard class libraries) and techniques for building graphical user interfaces and business logic. 152-169 JavaScript This course is an introduction to programming fundamentals using JavaScript. JavaScript is a client-side scripting language used for creating dynamic web applications. Fundamentals covered include variables, decisions, functions, events, loops and arrays. Use these fundamentals by applying them to a range of programs that solve personal and business problems with hands-on exercises. Cascading style sheets (CSS), hypertext markup language (HTML) and the document object model (DOM) will also be discussed. (If you have never programmed before, please take 152-107 first.) 152-109 .Net Web Development This course introduces the server-side of web application development, featuring the ASP.NET object model and the VB.Net programming language to build dynamic, database-connected web applications that are the foundation of modern e-commerce and e-Business functionality. Special emphasis is placed on client-server, n-tier application design and database architecture, programming and connectivity. Design, develop, implement and maintain a significant web application project. Other server-side application development environments (PHP, Cold Fusion, Perl, Java) will also be discussed and contrasted, along with client-side JavaScript, Cascading Style Sheets (CSS), Dynamic HTML (DHTML), XHTML and XML. Emphasis is placed on hands-on programming. 152-135 Advanced Java Programming Advanced Java Programming is an architecturally focused and programming intensive course in object-oriented analysis and design (OOA/DO). The course focuses on industry standard design patterns (GoF) and architectural best practices (programming to interfaces and using composition, e.g.) that lead to improved software quality, flexibility and maintainability. Agile software development methodologies such as the Rational Unified Process (RUP), Model-driven Development (MDD) and Test-driven Development (TDD) are also explored in depth. While the majority of information is presented in a Java context, some samples are also provided in VB.Net and C# to show that the concepts may be applied to any object-oriented language. Other advanced topics, such as multithreading, data structures, database programming and connectivity, and deployment practices, are also explored. 152-137 Mobile iOS App Development Get introduced to the exciting world of iPhone application development. Discussion topics include the iPhone SDK, the Cocoa Touch Framework, the Model View Controller (MVC) paradigm, the Objective C programming language, the Development tools ? XCode and Interface Builder, the iPhone Simulator, and core animation and graphic development for iPhone applications. This course is intended for anyone interested in learning more about iPhone applications, and how they are developed and used to increase productivity personally and professionally. 152-198 Distributed Java This course introduces advanced, distributed application development for both desktop and web-based systems, using the Java language and the Java Standard and Enterprise development kits. A distributed application is one where a program is divided into components and these components run on different computer systems. A web application is a common example of a distributed application. Advanced web development in Java is a key learning objective for this course. Students will learn to build enterprise class applications using server-side technologies including Java Servlets, JavaBeans, Enterprise Java Beans (EJB) and Web Services. In addition, advanced client-side programming using JavaScript and Cascading Stylesheets will be explored, including programming AJAX functionality. For distributed desktop development Java Remote Method Invocation will be explored. This course will also touch on popular open source frameworks such as Struts, Spring, Grails and Google Web Toolkit. 152-140 Android Application Development This course introduces you to Android Device application development. Discussion topics include the Google SDK, the Android programming environment, architecture, and tools. Students will create applications using XML-Based Layouts, Widgets, Containers and Lists. This course is intended for anyone interested in learning more about Android applications, how they are developed and used to increase productivity personally and professionally. 152-129 PHP1/Web Development This PHP programming course provides the knowledge necessary to design and develop dynamic, database-driven web pages using PHP. PHP is a language written for the web, quick to learn, easy to deploy and provides substantial functionality required for e-commerce. This course introduces the PHP framework and syntax, and it covers in depth the most important techniques used to build dynamic web sites. Perform hands-on practice with a MySQL database to create database-driven HTML forms and reports. 152-139 Web Development/PHP2 This PHP course is a continuation of the first that places emphasis on e-commerce skills including user authentication, data validation, dynamic data updates and shopping cart implementation. Also learn how to configure PHP on the Apache Web Server. description: The Department of Computer Science at the University of Alabama hosts a multi-week series of Computer Science summer. Students are taught multiple topics of Computer Science while learning to program a computer in several exciting contexts (robotics control and smartphone apps). The Computer Science camps are taught in a manner that encourages self-exploration across multiple projects.

name: Beowulf Boot Camp
description: This exciting course offers students and teachers a unique opportunity to work with advanced research technology not usually available in a typical classroom setting. During Beowulf Boot Camp 2013, students will work hands-on with a number of LSU professors as they learn how to build and use supercomputers. Open to Louisiana High School Students, Baton Rouge Community College Students, and Louisiana Teachers

name: DigiPen ProjectFUN Workshops
description: DigiPen Institute of Technology, the leader in video game development education, hosts summer workshops designed to introduce middle school, high school, and college students of all experience levels to the fundamentals of game programming, 3D computer animation and robotics. For over 15 years, we have offered our exciting two-week workshops at our college campus in Redmond, Washington, and at partner sites across the U.S. Come join the FUN!

name: DigiPen
description: DigiPen Institute of Technology has been dedicated to educating students interested in the field of interactive entertainment since 1988. Interactive digital entertainment is at the vanguard of technological innovation, and DigiPen leads the way to a serious career in this field and beyond. Our comprehensive program has been ranked the number one program in the world for Game Development by Electronic Gaming Monthly. DigiPen offers the following degrees: Bachelor of Science in Real-Time Interactive Simulation, Bachelor of Science in Computer Engineering, Bachelor of Fine Arts in Production Animation, and Master of Science in Computer Science. DigiPen's Redmond, Washington campus is located in the heart of one of the game industry's major development centers that is home to over 60 game development companies including Nintendo and Microsoft. With cooperation of major game industry leaders like Nintendo and Microsoft, DigiPen ensures that the educational experience is one that truly prepares students for the rigors of the industry.

name: CodeNow
description: CodeNow is a DC based non-profit focused on teaching underrepresented high school students foundational skills in computer programming through free extra curricular off campus trainings. This is essential because it lowers the barriers normally associated with programming by opening the door at an earlier stage when youths are just beginning to explore their options and opportunities.

name: Lake County Schools C++ Game Programming Course
description: Lake County Schools Technology Campus provides vocational/technical trains over 1500 high school students in Lake County Illinois. The C++ Game Programming Program based heavily on computer science and mathematics. Program participants are eligible for up to 8 college credits and participate in a rigorous program curriculum based on resource provided by DigiPen University. Enrollment FAQs here: http://www.techcampus.org/about/frequently_asked_questions

name: Purdue - Adventures in Computer Science Summer Camp
description: Purdue Adventures in CS Camp is open to students who are entering grades 6,7,or 8 by the Fall of 2012. No previous computer science or programming expertise is necessary, but campers should be comfortable using a computer. The camp will take an in-depth look at computer science concepts such as programming, cryptography, and robotics, and how they are used every day to make a difference in our world. Using programs such as Python, Alice, and Web design software, students will explore hands-on applications. Students will also participate in a PicoCricket design studio challenge.

name: IT is for Girls
description: The "IT is for Girls" workshop and summercamp of UNC Greensboro is aimed at increasing awareness about IT education and careers among high-school girls in grades 9 to 11, in collaboration with Guilford County Schools. Through hands-on activities, participants learn to create animations, interactive narratives, and video games using SCRATCH software from MIT, design web pages, explore computer and internet security, and investigate fun ways to visualize data. During lunch, working IT women professionals, from area firms and UNCG speak about education, career paths and opportunities in IT, balancing work and personal life, and how to be successful in technology careers.

name: TechPREP

A consortium of organizations will deliver an integrated program including a technology demonstration center, classroom teaching, and awareness-building and experimental events. Our aim is to connect young women with college students and local business people. A cohort of 6th, 7th, and 8th grade young women will be introduced to the practical aspects of computing, mathematics and physics, and engineering, through a series of Saturday programs and followed up with a two week summer day camp. The age group is chosen because continued achievement and a foundation of eventual success in the sciences starts early in a student's education.

name: feynlabs
levels: Elementary | Middle School | High School | College | Vocational
description: Feynlabs aims to teach the concepts of programming languages to kids (as opposed to a specific programming language). By abstracting the common elements of programming languages, our aim is to enable learners to rapidly learn any programming language. Our work has been covered in academic journals and also in leading education blogs like Edutopia. In the first six months of the launch of our page of Facebook, we have 40K fans. Currently, we are conducting trials in some schools in the UK and Europe. Feynlabs is creating a set of unique techniques to teach computer science to kids based on a) Teaching the concepts of Programming Languages to kids and b) Fostering an interest in Computer Science using the Raspberry Pi and other devices. c) Sharing content. We are a social enterprise because we share content with schools using Open source principles (i.e. for free) As pedagogy, I would consider it the re-application of Constructivist principles to the learning of Programming Languages and teaching of Computer Science in the age of the Internet. If I were to ask: What was the first programming language you learned? Depending on which era you started computing, the answer could be Basic in the 80s, Pascal in the 90s, Java/JavaScript at the turn of the century  But the point is: its always a specific programming language you began with. Fast forward a few years  if you did end up studying computer science, you studied the Concepts of Programming Languages or the Philosophy of Computer science at the Masters level for a computer science course What if you could switch the two? What if you could teach concepts of programming languages upfront  even to kids? This seemingly simple switch has many advantages. Learners have a fast on-ramp and interest. They learn at a unique pace and keep up interest. They see how programming applies to real life problems at a very early stage of their learning and they learn complex concepts of programming within a wider context Thus, our end goal is not to teach programming. Rather, it is to enable the participants to rapidly master any programming language and in doing so, explore computer science. Feynlabs is addressing a unique (not yet addressed) problem  which I can encapsulate as How do we take learners from 0 to 60 fast? i.e. accelerate the computer science learning at an early stage so that learners dont get bogged down and can quickly see the vista i.e. the big picture vision. From a learning standpoint this would useful because once the participant can see the big picture and they can add their own unique contribution/imagination to learning This leads to a different conversation in teaching. Instead of discussing endless variants of IF-THEN-ELSE statements and FOR loops, we have the freedom to explore the beauty and interconnectedness of Computer Science at an early stage. We can talk of hardware and software and algorithms holistically. We can introduce the principles of Systems thinking. We can prepare kids for the next way of computing by looking at a variety of computing devices (not just PCs). Thus, Feynlabs is preparing learners for a career in Computer Science. We focus on Raspberry Pi and Python as teaching platforms (but also work with others)

name: Zatna-Pingry- Programming Scratch
description: Pingry Hi-Tech camps are designed to provide students with an early advantage in computer science and engineering skills which they can use throughout their lives. In a supportive, age appropriate environment, we provide a dynamic experience for students who embrace intellectual challenges. We help students enhance their sense of logic while inspiring the curiosity that is essential in continuing the discovery and learning process. The computer science and engineering skills our campers will acquire from Pingry Hi-Tech camps will allow them to analyze, plan and solve different problems. As computer science and engineering skills are no longer limited to the realm of tech professionals, the earlier your child is exposed to and masters these skills, the greater the competitive advantage for them, regardless of the careers they will pursue later in life. This program is designed for campers with no robotics experience. The camp will use Lego Mindstorms NXT robots to give a first introduction to robotics. Campers will work with structurally sound building techniques, different types of sensors and motors, and elementary robotics programming using the NXT software. >> Participants: Grades 2-6 >> Dates: July 15th-July 19th >> Location: The Pingry School, Martinsville Campus, Smith Middle School M121 >> Time: 9:00 AM  4:30 PM >> Price: $600

description: Programming 2 course: Focuses on input/output, data types, conditionals, loops, methods and collections (arrays and arraylists) and some classes.

name: Montverde Academy
levels: Preschool | Elementary | Middle School | High School
description: Advanced Placement Computer Science (APCS) Approved by the college board. Students completing an AP course and score and three or more on the AP exam receive college credit from participating schools. APCS covers the basics of computer science; from first steps in learning to program in Java, to advanced topics such as inheritance, sorting and searching.

name: Barrington High School- Intro to Game Design
description: This is an introductory course in computer programming that begins by exploring the concepts of how computers work, how information is processed, and how programs allow the user to define and control a process. Starting with the animation of 3-D objects, and later by developing sophisticated computer games, students will learn higher level algorithmic thinking in a structured programming environment. Students will utilize easy to understand computer interfaces (ie drag and drop) without having to learn a specific computer programming language syntax. No prior programming experience is necessary.

name: Barrington High School-Intro to Robotics
description: This is an introductory course in language specific computer programming that begins with programming the movement of robots on a computer screen, followed by learning to program free standing robots. In this class students will learn to write their own computer programs from an object-oriented perspective. Number systems key to computer programming, flowcharting, algorithm development, structured programming, and step-wise refinement will follow. Students will study and learn to write programs in the Java programming language, with an emphasis on problem solving techniques. This class provides a solid programming foundation that students will find beneficial for AP Computer Science the following year. No prior programming experience is necessary.

name: Barrington High School- AP CS
description: AP Computer Science introduces students to the formal concepts of object-oriented computer programming, including program design, control structures, data structures and algorithms using the Java programming language. It is a year-long course designed to be comparable to a first year college level computer programming class. During the first semester students will gain an understanding of the history of computing, and the nature of hardware and software; the software design process, and the basics of object-oriented programming, as well as the ethical considerations of computer science. They will also gain a familiarity with Java classes, objects, and data types; basic Java syntax; constructor, accessor, and mutator methods; decision and looping statements; and logical operators, among others. During the second semester students will have the opportunity to further develop and refine their programming skills by focusing on the techniques of data abstraction, including encapsulation and inheritance. In particular, the emphasis is on the organization of information and the implementation of common data structures such as arrays and array lists, as well as various searching and sorting methods through such structures. Students also explore recursion and the close relationship between data structures and algorithms including basic complexity analysis and comparisons between several different methods.

name: Barrington High School
description: This course extends the concepts of AP Computer Science A by providing a survey of data structures and introduces and develops methods for designing and implementing abstract data types using the Java programming language. The main focus is on how to build and encapsulate data objects and their associated operations. In particular, the emphasis of this course is on the organization of information; the implementation of common data structures such as lists, stacks, queues, trees, and graphs, including linked structures, hash tables, and heaps, as well as elementary methods of complexity analysis applied to algorithms that manipulate dynamic and static data structures. This class covers the remaining topics found in the former AP Computer Science AB curriculum, and is designed to model a college level semester course in advanced data structures.

name: Thinkersmith
levels: Preschool | Elementary | Middle School | High School | College | Vocational

We bring everything needed, and teach the lesson in 30 minute to 50 minute segments. Visit http://www.thinkersmith.org/travelingCircuits.php to schedule one today.

name: Bloomfield High School
description: Computer Science for All - a computational science course open to high school students. This semester long course uses computer modeling as an introduction to computer science and computational thinking while exposing students to the breadth of applicability of computer science to solving real-world problems. Computer programming exercises and activities in an agent-based modeling environment (NetLogo) lead up to building computational science projects. Students will become familiar with the iterative design, build, and test development cycle common to computer science and engineering, and learn computer science constructs, processes and tools while creating models of local phenomena as complex systems. Students will also learn mathematics for modeling, probability and statistics, and data analysis techniques.

name: CodeNow
description: CodeNow is a non-profit, focused on teaching underrepresented high school students foundational skills in computer programming. We do this through free, extracurricular, off campus trainings. We work with students who receive the free or reduced-cost lunch, with an emphasis on girls. Our program is essential because it lowers the barriers normally associated with technology by giving students exposure to programming at an early age when they are beginning to explore their options and opportunities. Since launching in February of 2011, CodeNow has completed four cohorts of phase one of its program in Washington D.C. Providing more than 3,000 hours of free training to students in the programming language Ruby. In March 2013 , CodeNow will launch its first training in New York City. Over a six week period students will receive 40+ hours of in person training held on the weekends and 10 hours of homework. During which they have an opportunity to earn a netbook by arriving on time, finishing homework and completing projects. After the training students are encouraged to participate in the alumni community where they are invited to attend monthly meetups and field trips. As alumni they receive mentoring and assistance finding internships.

name: Skema Education
levels: Elementary | Middle School | High School | College
description: Skema is a start-up company in Iceland founded by Rakel Solvadottir in july 2011. Skema believes it has a unique answer to the lack of tech people. The solution is to start as early as in primary school to plant a seed with the children that technology can be; fun, interesting, and anyone can become a technical wizard. Young children do not have preconceived ideas like adults about technology, and are ready to try anything as long as it is fun and interesting. This is why Skema wants to spark interest in technology by teaching children how to program their own computer games. In order to achieve the desired results, Skema has developed its own methodology on how to teach children and even adults computer programming. The methodology is continuously improved in cooperation with academia and in-house research team.
languages: Alice | C++ | HTML | Java | Javascript | Kodu | Lua | Mobile Apps | Python

name: Steer
description: Steer is devoted to teaching the fundamentals of web design and development. At our space in Clerkenwell, we give you the skills you need to create awesome websites and apps. Get a fantastic new career, create your own start-up, or make an idea come to life online. We teach practical Javascript and jQuery, Ruby on Rails, HTML and CSS, user experience and responsive web design. Our courses range from all-day intensive classes, to 2 hour evening classes held once a week. Our courses are for anyone who is interested in learning web development and design, whether you're a complete beginner or are looking to advance the skills you already have. All-day workshops: Learn jQuery, 3 day workshop, Monday 18th March - Wednesday 20th March. Learn HTML and CSS, 3 day workshop, Monday 25th March - Wednesday 27th March.Learn HTML and Front-End Web Development, 5 day workshop, Monday 8th April - Friday 12th April. Ruby on Rails, 5 day workshop, Monday 22nd April - Friday 26th April. Learn User Experience Design, 1 day workshop, Saturday 27th April. Responsive Web Design and Designing for the Mobile Web, 1 day workshop, Saturday 4th May. Learn jQuery, 3 day workshop, Monday 6th May - Wednesday 8th May. Afterschool / Afterwork programs: Learn HTML and CSS, evening program 6.30pm - 8.30pm, every Tuesday for 8 weeks, starting Tuesday 26th March. Learn jQuery, evening program 6.30pm - 8.30pm, every Wednesday for 8 weeks, starting Wednesday 27th March. Learn Ruby on Rails evening program 6.30pm - 8.30pm, every Thursday for 8 weeks, starting Thursday 28th March
languages: Css | HTML | Javascript | Mobile Apps | Ruby

name: App Academy
description: App Academy is an intensive, full-time, web development class in San Francisco and New York City. Over nine weeks, you'll learn all the skills needed to begin a career as a web developer. Through hands-on projects, we train you to build modern Ruby on Rails web applications. Programming experience isn't required; you will need lots of tenacity and a passion for building cool stuff. App Academy is as low-risk as we can make it. You only pay us if you find a job as a developer after the program. In that case, the fee is 15% of your first year salary, payable over the first 6 months after you start working. We're in this together; we only succeed if the program works for you. 93% of our graduates have offers or are working in tech jobs now at an average salary of $83,000. Hiring companies include: Facebook, Zendesk, Twilio, Carbon Five and Thoughtbot.

name: Ideaventions
levels: Preschool | Elementary | Middle School | High School
description: Ideaventions is a science and technology enrichment center geared to children ages 3 to 13. We teach a range of science, technology, engineering and mathematics classes throughout the year at our Science Center located at the Hunter Mill Plaza in Oakton, Virginia. We also run science camps, do after-school programs at local schools, develop new STEM curriculum and lots more. Ideaventions is a place where no idea is too crazy and where children, the adults of tomorrow, learn that anything is possible with a little creativity. Our hands-on labs are led by experienced teachers who emphasize divergent thinking and seek to harness a childs natural curiosity about our world. Our programs are designed to share and nurture childrens love for the sciences. Current Schedule Available at http://www.ideaventions.com/Labs.html

name: ForgeJS
description: ForgeJS is a new Seattle based organization dedicated to teaching full stack JavaScript application development. ForgeJS is announcing a series of three intensive weekend workshops. Advanced JavaScript, March 22-24, is a launch pad for developers who haven't gone beyond jQuery and the DOM, covering skills, concepts and patterns foundational to building large scale JavaScript applications. Node, March 29-31, covers the foundations of backend development with Express, socket.io and workflow management with Grunt, in addition to presenting an accessible first look at the Node API and the concepts needed to master it. Backbone, April 5-7, covers all the core concepts of client-side, event driven JavaScript web application development using one of the most flexible, popular JavaScript MVC libraries. Each weekend features world class mentors in an intimate setting (enrollment is limited to 24 students) and is rooted in hands on, project-based learning: you'll be coding from the minute the workshops start, with breaks for conceptual overviews and food catered onsite. All events are hosted at HUB Seattle, in Pioneer Square. Visit forgejs.com to register and find out more.

name: DALEWARES INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY
description: Dalewares Institute of Technology came into existence in June 2007 as a result of a major change in policy direction in the area of education by the Federal Government of Nigeria. The government having come full circle realized that in order to transform the Nigerian economy, private sector participation can no longer be ignored in manpower development and transformation of the Nigerian citizen in various endeavous especially in entrepreneurial abilities . The Federal Ministry of Education under the then Hon. Minister, Ms Obi Ezekwesili came up with the Innovative Enterprise Institutions (IEIs) and Vocational Enterprise Institutions (VEIs) in collaboration with the National Board for Technical Education (NBTE) as an offshoot of the Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) The Institute was therefore conceived by its Board of Governing Council under the chairmanship of Mr. Olusegun Babalola under the IEI/VEI scheme to train and develop students and to award to them on completion the National Innovation Diploma (NID) / National Diploma (ND) to its graduating students The accreditation further confers on the institution, the added bonus of being listed in the Joint Admission and Matriculation Board (JAMB) prospectus as a bonafide approved Polytechnic institution. All intending students would therefore be required to sit for the JAMB examination to be able to secure admission for its courses. Dalewares Institute of Technology,an industry focused polytechnic is a first of its kind in sub-Saharan Africa (excluding the Republic of South Africa), that is granted license to run a full on-campus two (2) year program in the following ICT based programs which includes Multimedia Technology, Software Engineering, Hardware Engineering and Network and System Security. This course is expected to train students and other interested candidates with other higher qualifications to become professionals. The Institution is privately run, fee-paying, with the objective of providing quality training services to the Nigerian knowledge market in the area of Information Technology by building a strong brand that will be international in scope, with strong alliances The emphasis is on capacity building to explore the full potential of the individual and to bridge the knowledge gap presently existing in the IT world. Furthermore, research and developmental programs are expected to go hand in hand with the training.

Three UW Computer Science courses are offered: Computer Science Principles (CSE 120) Introduces fundamental concepts of computer science and computational thinking. Includes logical reasoning, problem solving, data representation, abreaction, the creation of "digital artifacts" such as web pages and programs, managing complexity, operation of computers and networks, effective web searching, ethical, legal, and social aspects of information technology. Computer Programming I (CSE 142) Basic concepts for programming-in-the-small abilities and concepts including procedural programming (methods, parameters, return values), basic control structures (sequence, if/else, for loop, while loop), file processing, arrays and an introduction to defining objects. Computer Programming II (CSE 143) Concepts of data abstraction and encapsulation including stacks, queues, linked lists, binary trees, recursion, instruction to complexity, and use of predefined collection classes. Interested high school administrators and teachers can review the steps to bring UW Computer Science coursework to their schools, and contact the UWHS office. http://www.uwhs.washington.edu/uwhs/teachers/

name: The Iron Yard Academy
description: What will you be capable of by the end of the class? You will be qualified as a professional, junior-level JavaScript and front-end engineer. Join a startup and get a solid prototype off the ground quickly and efficiently Build digital products for web development shop, agency, etc. Build non-trivial, fast, efficient, production-quality apps Build gorgeous websites Most importantly, learn how to learn You won't know absolutely everything there is to know, but we will ensure that you know how to learn it if you need to. Excerpts from the curriculum Here's just a small sample from the curriculum. You'll learn HTML, CSS, and JavaScript from the ground up become awesome at using Git for version control get totally comfortable working with command line tools learn to write jQuery plugins from scratch get hands-on experience with the newest HTML5 tech build non-trivial, production quality JS apps with Backbone.js work with languages that compile down to JS, like CoffeeScript and ClojureScript learn your way around Rails, with a focus on what's important to know for frontend work in Rails apps. build apps that run lean and fast on both desktop and mobile browsers and much more ;) What kind of students are we looking for? Before we get into specifics, we need to let you know that this class is going to be challenging. Material will get really hard, really quickly. All of the work is very do-able, but if you think you're going to develop professional level skills in a cushy 40 hour week, this isn't the place for you. (We estimate you'll put in about 60.) We're family people, so our goal is for you to work as hard as possible in class so you can find balance in a great job when you're done. We're really excited about the different types of people who are going to apply, and we don't have stereotypes of what a developer is like. Here are a few things we'll look for: Hard worker - Like we said above, this won't be a walk in the park. Prepare for a rigorous course. Self motivated - If you need to be managed, this isn't the place for you. Works well with others - you'll be assigned to groups for projects, and each person's role will be crucial. Interested in learning, even if you know some code Even if you know basics, you might have to unlearn some things. We'll start from the ground up as a team, and there won't be room for egos. Graceful problem solver - We'll work on some hard stuff, and patience is a must. Ready to have fun - We work hard, play hard, and laugh every single day. We do the best work we possibly can, but we make sure not to take ourselves too seriously. What will the schedule look like? Monday through Thursday: Class starts at 9am 9am - 12pm: lecture time 12pm - 1pm: lunch 1pm - ?pm: lab work Some days might include afternoon lectures Lectures: Lessons will be fast-paced, interactive, and funny. Hopefully. The goal is for you to absorb a whole lot of information, then apply it on a real project during lab. Lunch: Working hard requires resting hard, so we try to enjoy lunch as much as possible - whether we're heating leftovers or heading to Barley's for a slice and a pint. From our space you can walk or bike to the river, parks, amazing coffee, tasty food, or craft beer, and we like to take advantage of that access. Lab work: In lab you'll be working on real websites and apps that real people will use - not scripted assignements. We're partnering with the city, non-profits, and other organizations who have problems that we can help solve. (Life in Greenville is a great example.) You'll have access to the space 24 hours a day, just in case you need to burn some midnight oil. Fridays: Catch up day Open lab time with the instructor (9am-5pm) Time with The Iron Yard Mentors when they're in town Fridays will be a chance to breathe, take a break from intense lectures, and catch up if you need to. If Iron Yard Mentors are in town, we'll be able attend their talks and spend time with them when possible. (They're awesome people with a lot to offer. See for yourself.) We'll also strongly encourage you to contribute to open source projects, build your own stuff, and learn new languages. When you're done with your work from class, of course.

description: The ultimate vision of our company is to have a nationwide school for web based technologies that bring together the conventional education system and leaders within the technology industry. The technical field is clearly growing at a rapid rate and the demand for developers is considerably larger than the number of qualified candidates. A large majority of students graduate from college without marketable hard skills. These students often find themselves struggling to find employment regardless of their undergraduate degrees. With this company, not only will we be filling the industry need for new developers, but we will offer opportunities to people who are looking them. DevJumpstart is a school system based in Austin Texas in which students with no technical backgrounds learn to develop software. Within 10 weeks, our program will have our students ready to apply to entry-level positions for startups within Austin. Our curriculum is based off of research conducted with Austin based startups. When conducting this research we approached a number of prominent startups and asked them what hard skills they needed developers to have. As a result, we will help our students get job placement by working closely with Austin based startups.

name: Algonquin Regional High School
description:
Course Listings: Python programming Introduction to Computer Programming C++ I Programming C++ II Programming Game Development Using XNA AP Computer Science HTML/Webpage Development Students interested in programming can also join our Computer Programming Team! This is a place where you can explore many different interests in the field of computer programming. Students in that club also attend regional programming competitions throughout New England. There are multiple types of activities we will do in programming club. First, there is learning and/or improving your programming skills in any way you want. You can spend time during meetings working on software you are writing. This is helpful because you can talk to fellow programmers for help. We will also be practicing for competitions. We also compete in programming competitions with teams from other schools and have one most of the regional events. These are competitions where you will go with the team to solve interesting and challenging programming problems. Also, free pizza and ice cream. Additionally, we annually take on the challenge of writing a piece of software as a whole team, often in the form of a video game. This will require you to use all your skills, not just programming! This can include art, music, story-writing, math, or anything you can imagine that can be added as an element in a video game. But I don't know how to code! How do I start? That is not a problem. Learning a programming language is fun and rewarding. In programming club, we primarily use the languages C++ and Java. It is easy to pick up on the basics from online tutorials and you can learn a lot from others in the club.

name: Verona High School
description: Courses Offered at Verona High School include: FUNDAMENTALS OF COMPUTER SCIENCE 1 Semester, 2.5 credits Prerequisite: None Students learn the fundamentals of software engineering. Students will design, code, and test computer programs using the Alice programming language. Alice is an innovative 3D programming environment developed by Carnegie Mellon University in which beginner students can create an animation to tell a story, to create an interactive game, or to create a working model a real-world situation. Alice uses 3D graphics and a drag-and-drop interface to facilitate a more engaging, less frustrating introduction to Computer Science. AP COMPUTER SCIENCE Full Year, 5 credits Prerequisite: Fundamentals of Computer Science or Supervisor Approval Students will use the Java programming language to learn object-oriented programming with a concentration on problem solving and algorithm development. This course is aligned with the College Boards Advanced Placement Computer Science A course and examination and is the equivalent of a first-semester college-level course in Computer Science. Students will write, run and debug object-oriented software, develop and select appropriate algorithms and data structures to solve problems, and learn to read and understand large programs consisting of many software components. Student must take the AP exam to earn AP course credit. HONORS ADVANCED TOPICS IN COMPUTER SCIENCE Full Year, 5 credits Prerequisite: AP Computer Science This course uses an interdisciplinary approach, where students apply their computer science knowledge to solve real-world problems in other disciplines. The course highlights the role of computing in applied mathematics, engineering, the physical and biological sciences, finance, and computer science itself, emphasizing how these disciplines are intertwined in the modern world. Students will apply their knowledge of software engineering developed in prior computer science courses to solve classic problems in these disciplines. Students will also learn how to use more advanced data structures and algorithms in solving these problems. SOFTWARE ENGINEERING: MOBILE DEVICES 1 Semester, 2.5 credits Prerequisite: Honors Advanced Topics in Computer Science This course introduces mobile application development for the Android platform. Students will learn skills for creating and deploying Android applications, with particular emphasis on software engineering topics including software architecture, software process, usability, and deployment. Students will create and deploy an Android application as the culminating activity of the course. SOFTWARE ENGINEERING: GAME DEVELOPMENT 1 Semester, 2.5 credits Prerequisite: Honors Advanced Topics in Computer Science Students will use software engineering skills developed in prior coursework to develop 2-D and 3-D games. Computer game development requires many facets of Computer Science, including Computer Graphics, Algorithms, Data Structures, Networking, and Human-Computer Interaction. It also requires knowledge of other disciplines including Economics, Mathematics, Physics, and Psychology. Students will create and deploy 2-D or 3-D game as the culminating activity of the course.

name: 'Yes We Can' Community Center
description: Udacity CS101 Start: 9/2013. Have a nice summer. This program introduces Computer Science and software development through the udacity.com CS101 course. It is nominally an 8-week course, self-paced, based on short video clips and many small quizzes, which are just for practice. No prior experience is assumed. You'll be introduced to the Python programming language and by the end of the course, you'll have written your own web-search engine. The course is self-paced so you proceed at whatever speed you are comfortable with, and we're available to answer questions and to keep you motivated. The Yes We Can Community Center (Garden St., New Cassel) provides the computers and networking that you'll need. You should bring a paper notebook and pen, and be prepared to commit to stick with the course, several hours per week. Along the way, we hope you have fun. By the end, you will have earned a certificate of completion, and have learned if computer science is a field that interests you. The Web has plenty of follow-on courses, so you can continue with software development and Computer Science if you find you like it. For CS101, we'll help you with the material and we hope you'll help your fellow learners taking the course. The course has an online forum where you can ask and answer questions posed by CS101 students from all around the world. The course is in English and all members of the North Hempstead community center are welcome to study with us. It's all online, no textbook is required. Ever wished your teacher had a Pause and Rewind button? Well, in this course they do! Unsure if this course will interest you? Well, come out and take a look. Tell us what you seek and ask us about CS101. Are you a self-starter? If you have Internet access and a PC, feel free to dive into the course on your own. The forum is available to help you. http://rdrewd.blogspot.com/search/label/udacity has articles that might interest you.

name: IMACS - Institute for Mathematics and Computer Science (Plantation, FL)
description: COMPUTER PROGRAMMING AND VIRTUAL ROBOTICS - (a) Computer Programming: Students learn to write computer programs with LOGO, a graphic-based computer programming language developed at MIT. With individualized guidance, students are challenged by projects designed by the IMACS Curriculum Development Group. (This class also serves as the ideal introduction to the more advanced university-level Computer Science class.) (b) Virtual Robotics: Students use a toolbox of wheels, gears and sensors to design, build and program robots. The robots themselves operate in a virtual world that mirrors the physical world, complete with friction and laws governing conservation of momentum and energy. Students learn to succeed in this course by analyzing and working through the challenging problems they encounter. UNIVERSITY COMPUTER SCIENCE - The IMACS Computer Science program is second to none in its ability to engage talented secondary school students with challenging, university-level curriculum that focuses on computational thinking and go well beyond just coding. Students who complete this sequence of classes develop a deep understanding of core concepts while becoming fluent in four programming languages (Scheme, Haskell, Python and Java). The IMACS approach provides students with a unique academic advantage in college and beyond. AP COMPUTER SCIENCE - A comprehensive Java programming course leading to the Advanced Placement Computer Science exam. This course is qualified through the College Board's rigorous AP Course Audit process.

name: The Mount Washington School
description: Programming With Scratch is designed to be a 10-week introduction to basic programming concepts for 4th through 7th graders. This after-school session will be held from February 6th, 2013 to April 10th, 2013 and the class will meet once a week on Wednesdays from 3:15pm to 4:15pm at the Mount Washington School Upper Building computer lab. Each class session will consist of about 15-20 minutes of lecture where we will cover specific programming, math, or software engineering topics. We will then use the remainder of the session (about 45 minutes) to build the assignment of the day. The primary emphasis is on how to use programming to solve problems. Mathematical concepts will be covered as necessary but a basic fluency in the following is recommended: cartesian coordinate systems, geometry, concept of negative numbers, and some pre-algebra. You will be taught all the math you need to know.

name: The Marvelwood School
description: Introduction to Computing The course covers concepts and application of programming, and problem solving. Topics include programming basics, functions/subroutines, arrays, program flow (loops, conditionals) and basic I/O functions. The focus of the course is to introduce students to the world of programing -- with emphasis on how programing is used in business and not necessarily on game programing, but elements of that genre are explored. This is a year-long course, broken into three sections. The first section covers HTML/JavaScript through the use of student-created projects using Microsoft's Visual Web Developer Express platform. The students learn how to use the Integrated Development Environment (IDE) to build web pages, and to incorporate JavaScript into those pages. The course covers the commonly used page elements such as text boxes, radio buttons, check boxes, buttons, and discusses the JavaScript programming language and how it is used within web pages. To illustrate the concepts, students build web pages for fictional companies (e.g. restaurant surveys). The second section covers Visual Basic using Microsoft's Visual Basic .Net Express platform. The students learn how to use the Integrated Development Environment (IDE) to develop fully functional windows-based programs. The course covers the commonly used windows-based elements such as text boxes, buttons, drop down lists, menus, dialog boxes, as well as the Basic programming language. To illustrate the concepts, the students create their own Notepad (a simple text editor) and a functional, lightweight web browser. The third section covers Visual C# using Microsoft's Visual C# .Net Express platform. The students learn how to use this Integrated Development Environment (IDE) to develop fully functional windows-based programs. The course covers the commonly used windows-based elements such as text boxes, buttons, drop down lists, menus, dialog boxes, as well as the C# programming language. To illustrate the concepts, the students create their own calculator and a lightweight version of Windows Media player -- an application that will let the students organize and play music files.

description: Centriqs TechSmart KC Application Developer program is an accelerated, hands-on four month training program that provides students that have little or no technology experience with the programming skills required to obtain an entry-level programming job in Kansas City. The program focuses on Microsofts C# .NET programming language. Classes are 8:30- 4:30 five days a week for approximately four months. Classes are limited to 11 students. Students receive a laptop as part of the program and are required to create and present a secure ASP.NET web form application project and a secure ASP.NET MVC application project in order to complete the program. The TechSmart KC Application Developer program is comprised of the following five day classes:  C# .NET Fundamentals 1  C# .NET Fundamentals 2  HTML/CSS/jQuery  ASP1: ASP Fundamentals  ASP2: Membership and State Management  Relational Database Design & SQL  ASP3: Data Driven Applications  ASP4: Data Driven Applications and LINQ  ASP5: Web Services, jQuery & C# Advanced  ASP.NET - Alternative Frameworks  Mobile Development  Project Week 1: Web Forms  Project Week 2: MVC Project & Presentation

This training is intended to lead to employment in the computing industry, or transfer to a baccalaureate institution for continued study in the field, and to provide advanced study for computing professionals. Career opportunities include applied scientist, communications technician, computer maintenance technician, computer operator, data base specialist, documentation specialist, information specialist, Local Area Network (LAN) administrator, PC specialist, programmer, software engineer, software technician, systems analyst, systems test engineer, technician support representative, and as sales personnel skilled in marketing methods for computer systems. name: University of Canterbury - Computer Science Club
description: The Computer Science Club is a club aimed for students in years 7 to 10 who enjoy working with computers, and wish to learn to program, or extend their programming skills and explore the field of computer science! Students will have the opportunity to have programming tuition (for beginners and more experienced students), listen to talks from experts (both from the university and industry), and work on goals for badges. This club is intended for those who aren't yet doing NCEA but would like to get started on learning about the exciting world of programming and computer science. The only requirement to join the club is enthusiasm to learn more about computing and a positive attitude to learning. The club is run by academic staff and tutors from the department of Computer Science and Software Engineering. The department is known internationally for its work on computer science education (including the popular csunplugged.org), and has been heavily involved in designing standards for computing in NCEA. The club team is working in collaboration with the US-based CS Field Guide group, to develop a project for earning badges by achieving specific goals in the Computer Science Field. We run the club weekly after school, and offer three different days to come. We meet on Mondays, Wednesdays and Thursdays, with an extra girls only club, lead by girls, on Wednesday afternoon. We start at 3:30pm and finish at 5:00pm, however students can arrive from 3:00pm, and stay until 5:30pm. We meet in the Erskine building on the University Campus, there is limited paid coupon parking available (parking is free after 5pm). Come inside to Level 1 (by the cafe) and follow the signs! We meet during school terms and stop during holiday periods.

name: Encinal High School
description: Exploring Computer Science Prerequisite: Algebra 1 Exploring Computer Science is designed to introduce students to the breadth of the field o f computer science through an exploration of engaging and accessible topics. Rather than focusing the entire course on learning particular software tools or programming languages, the course is designed to focus the conceptual ideas of computing and help students understand why certain tools or languages might be utilized to solve particular problems. This is a yearlong course consisting of 6 units, approximately 6 weeks each. Assignments and instructions are contextualized to be socially relevant and meaningful for diverse students.

name: Encinal High School
description: CS PRINCIPLES Grades 10-12 credits Prerequisite: Algebra 1- recommended Exploring Computer Science Computing has changed the world in profound ways. It has opened up wonderful new ways for people to connect design, research, play, create, and express themselves. However, just using a computer is only a small part of the picture. The real transformative and empowering experience comes when one learns how to program the computer, to translate ideas into code. Students will focus on some of the Big Ideas of computing, such as abstraction, design, recursion, concurrency, simulations, and the limits of computation. Students will study applications of computing that have changed the world, talk about the history of computing, and where it will go in the future. Throughout the course, relevance is emphasized: relevance to the student and to society.

description: The UC Davis Center for Integrated Computing and STEM Education (C-STEM) aims to improve computing, science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (C-STEM) education in both formal and informal programs in K-14. The goal of the C-STEM Center is to provide computing education for all K-12 students and develop students' critical thinking and problem-solving skills through integrated computing and STEM education. The C-STEM Center studies how to use computing and robotics technology to increase student interest and help them learn STEM subjects with an emphasis on Algebra, the gatekeeper for STEM disciplines. The C-STEM Center also studies how to streamline the curriculum on computing education in the context of STEM subjects in elementary, middle, and high schools, as well as the first two years of college. Through various outreach activities including RoboPlay Competitions, the C-STEM Center seeks to inspire students to pursue computing and STEM related careers and post-secondary study.

The BE focuses on the design and implementation of real-world systems and gives an essential grounding in business and management skills. A work placement in a relevant industry is part of the degree, typically taken in the summers after the second and third years of study. This, along with a group project in your third year and an industry-driven project in your fourth year, gives real-life experience with practical aspects of engineering design and development. Victorias BE programme requires you to include three related courses that provide some knowledge and expertise in a field that complements your specialisation. Examples of subjects that you might choose would be Information Systems or Management to give your programme an entrepreneurial leaning, or Asian Studies to prepare yourself for overseas projects. The BE will open a wide range of careers including electronics, robot design, systems development, hardware development, programming, systems management, and research. name: NYC Generation Tech
description: GenTech is a tech-entrepreneurship program that provides hands-on learning experiences and mentorship opportunities for NYC high school students interested in transforming the world through tech-based innovations. Developed by the Network for Teaching Entrepreneurship (NFTE), the New York City Economic Development Corporation, and supported by Microsoft and other major partners, GenTech is built around the following four components that seek to educate and inspire students to pursue careers in entrepreneurship and technology: 1) Summer Programming: In a two-week tech-entrepreneurship bootcamp, students learn about technology fundamentals, including computer programming and 3D printing, as well as how to write a business plan and lean startup methodologies. Students develop basic knowledge of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript and form teams to develop a mobile app and business plan aimed at improving education or the quality of city life for NYC students. Using the foundational skills from the bootcamp, students focus on building out their mobile app and business plans for another six weeks with a mix of evening mentoring sessions and group and independent work. Throughout the summer, students are exposed to the NYC tech startup ecosystem through guest speakers and field trips. (July-August) 2) Mentorship & Enterprise Discovery: : Students receive mentorship from local business/technology undergraduate and graduate students during the bootcamp phase. After the bootcamp, each student team is paired with a small team of Tech Mentors from industry-leading tech and business organizations. Tech Mentors provide support, insight, and guidance to students during evening mentoring sessions. Mentoring sessions are held at various tech-related companies throughout NYC. 3) Demo Night & Awards Ceremony: In September, students demo and pitch their finished apps and business plans to a panel of prominent judges from the technology and venture capitalist community. Members of the winning team receive cash prizes and all students are honored at an awards ceremony. Hackathons: During the fall and early winter, GenTech students will participate in mobile app hackathons alongside professional developers and designers so that students can further develop skills in coding and design, gain more experience of working with tech professionals, and continue to build a network within the tech and startup sectors. 4) Hackathons: During the fall and early winter, GenTech students participate in mobile app hackathons alongside professional developers and designers so that students further develop skills in coding and design, gain more experience of working with tech professionals, and continue to build a network within the tech and startup sectors.

Use email for all correspondence. Our philosophy: Today's computers are more like a box of crayons than a calculator. Major math skills are no longer required. The key is to make it fun, provide encouragement and gentle guidance, then let them be creative with coding. Check out our site. http://www.creativecoding4kids.com

name: HEAT Institute by Stanford alumni
description: HEAT is an academic and professional development institute based in Silicon Valley dedicated towards the advancement of the humanities, entrepreneurship and technology, with curriculum developed in collaboration with members of QSci Lab at the Center for the Study of Language and Information at Stanford University. Our programs operate in Palo Alto just two blocks from the home of the late Steve Jobs. We are building a platform for students, educators, and professionals across disparate fields to enhance interdisciplinary knowledge discovery and innovation with a curricular focus on Big Data and Data Science applications. HEAT started the world's first dedicated Data Science course for high school and undergraduate students in 2011-2012, offering students an insider's introduction to curriculum that is now making the rounds in the Harvard Business Review, the Wall Street Journal, Forbes, the New York Times, and in new institutions that have emerged in 2013. Just as Bill Hewlett and Dave Packard founded the very "birthplace of Silicon Valley" in their Palo Alto garage, the HEAT team believes academic and professional educators perform their best in an environment in which they can freely design and teach new curricula. We work closely with individual professors, teachers, entrepreneurs, researchers, and professionals from Stanford, Harvard, Yale, Princeton, Oxford, UC Berkeley, USF, Google, Facebook, Apple, Intel, and a number of other Silicon Valley institutions currently facing a critical shortage of Big Data and Data Science talent. We are committed to providing future generations innovative curricula and pedagogy not found at any single institution. Data Science is an emerging field using Big Data that relies heavily on the expertise of other fields to help us make better decisions. Research by the McKinsey Global Institute (MGI) (Big Data: The next frontier for innovation, competition, and productivity) forecasts a 50 to 60 percent gap between the supply and demand of people with deep analytical talent in big data. Big Data is predicted to create over 4.4 million jobs globally by 2015, and the HEAT Institute aims to prepare students of all backgrounds for "the sexiest job of the 21st century," according to the Harvard Business Review, the Wall Street Journal, Forbes, and the New York Times. Previously obscured as a subset of computer science, Data Science is actually an accessible way for students and professionals outside of computer science to harness the latest tools in software engineering. The techniques, theories, logic, ideas and vocabulary of any field (including medicine, law, public policy, finance, and education) can be stored and used as data, which serves as the lifeblood of software engineering. The demand for data scientists is as, if not more, pressing as the need for computer scientists. HEAT SV is launching a new data science core with the help of Google's Visualization API and datasets to prepare future graduates in any field for the new economy. So where do we find tomorrow's Data Science superheroes? According to the Wall Street Journal: "Not from universities, it seems. Nigel Shadbolt, who doubles up as the professor of artificial intelligence at the University of Southampton as well as co-director of the U.K.'s Open Data Institute, said the courses don't yet exist. 'Bits of it do exist in various departments around the country, and also in businesses, but as an integrated discipline it is only just starting to emerge.'" The HEAT Institute aims to nurture creativity and critical thinking in students around the world by offering a core humanities curriculum, business and technology practica, and a platform for building interdisciplinary applications of knowledge. In the data science core, students will: -Learn about big data and relevant technologies -Learn about databases and structured query language (SQL) -Practice the extract, transform, load process used by every technology company using programming languages such as Python, PHP, and JavaScript and tools such as Pentaho Data Integration. -Learn how to tell stories with data and use data as the basis of your own startup company -Attend a field trip to a Silicon Valley company that uses large datasets on a day-to-day basis Participants will also do one of the following: -Build complex extract, transform, and load processes on large datasets such as US patents and US trademarks datasets provided by Google -Build their own portfolio of dynamic data visualizations using Google API and Tableau -Build their own functional "Facebook" social networking website -Build a search engine using US Patent And Trademark Data provided by Google

name: Casey-Westfield High School
description: The Mid-American Programming Group was founded by Julie Littlejohn, the computer/business teacher at Casey-Westfield High School in Casey, IL. One of the classes Mrs. Littlejohn taught was Introduction to Programming, where students learned fundamental, foundational, and practical programming skills. Some of the students in this class wanted to learn more about programming, but no Advanced Programming class was offered by the school. Mrs. Littlejohn approached Willy Farrell, a friend who had been programming professionally for more than 30 years (including many years at IBM), and asked him if he would facilitate an afterhours program to provide Advanced Programming training to her interested students. Being a card-carrying member of the Mrs. Littlejohn Fan Club himself, he agreed to do it, free of charge, and on his own time. Currently, Willy Farrell heads the programming group, and because she is retired and pursuing other interests, Mrs. Littlejohn is not as involved in the group as she once was. All inquiries about the group should be made to Willy, though all still warmly regard Julie Littlejohn as our Founder. The group started with one student, and called itself the Learning Java Advanced Programming Group. Soon after starting, another student joined the group. Later, a member was added who was still taking the Introduction to Programming class while participating, so Advanced was dropped from the title. Willy quickly realized there was a problem with group members getting enough computer time to complete their assigned exercises. To solve this, he bought every member of the group a small but adequate laptop. Willy understands that group members are the best and brightest from Casey-Westfield High School and are involved in a lot of activities, so an excuse by a member that he or she didn't get an assignment done because of extracurricular activities is readily accepted. But he will not accept these excuses: 1) I didn't get the assignment done because I didn't understand it. Not acceptable  every group member has the phone number and email address of Willy. Members can call or write Willy night and day if they have a problem or need some help; 2) I didnt get enough computer time to finish the assignment. Not acceptable  Willy got you a laptop to prevent that possibility. Initially, the group was meeting every Sunday at 1PM at a local fast-food restaurant where they could usually find a booth. But the booths were rather small and it was difficult to juggle textbooks and laptops. And it was a bit loud. The group needed a bigger, quieter place. Plus, the group was made aware of a YouTube video about coding/programming (willyfarrell.com/coders) that inspired them to try and grow. Enter Pastor Michael Kasting of Trinity Lutheran Church. When asked if the programmers could use the conference room in his church, he readily consented. His remarks were: When I was approached about the possibility of using the facilities of Trinity Lutheran Church for a programming class for high school students, I was glad to make our facility available. The kids need a quiet space to gather. God has blessed us with quiet space in abundance. It makes sense to share it! With our schools facing a financial crunch, were glad we can help in this very practical way. It will be exciting to see what comes from this venture. With a place that gave the group room to expand, the group decided to make that growth happen. So as not to exclude anyone, the group changed its name to the Mid-American Programming Group. New members to the group still begin by learning Java, a very popular programming language. But after that they learn C#, a popular Microsoft programming language. The goal is to get members certifications in these languages. A certification isn't a college degree (though members are consistently encouraged to go to college), but a certification can make the resume of a college graduate more appealing to employers. After Java and C#, there are a multitude of Web design languages and techniques that can be explored and mastered, and the group is setting out to do just that. The programming group also doesn't want to limit itself to only those in Casey, which is part of the reason for the name change. When we reach a certain point in our learning, we would like to do free software projects for local organizations, with our preference being charitable and not-for-profit institutions. Please watch the video at willyfarrell.com/coders. Its only 9 minutes long and is a real eyeopener about the importance of what the Mid-American Programming Group is doing. What the group is doing is good for our community; programmers often get jobs where they can work from home, so our best and brightest can stay right here in Casey. And what the group is doing is good for our young people  did you catch the part in the video where 1.4 million programming jobs will be created but only 400,000 U.S. students will get the required training for those jobs? Lets give our young people the opportunity to get one of those jobs that will be created and drive the economy of the future. It costs about $500 to add a member to the group  laptop, mouse, textbook, thumb drive. Up to now, Willy has borne those expenses, and happily. But Willy can only afford to add one member every month or two, say 8 or 9 per year. That pace is too slow for the group to have the kind of community impact for which it is striving. The teachers at the high school have identified upwards of a dozen students that would benefit by being in the group. They are also reaching out to high schools in nearby towns to identify students in those schools that would like to join the group. If they all came at once, Willy could not afford to equip each one of them. With $10,000, 20 students could join the group. The group needs help raising those kinds of funds. Wont you help the Mid-American Programming Group add members and give them the tools and equipment they need for success? Michael Leichty Contact Info: Phone: 217-932-2175 Email: mleichty@cw.k12.il.us Willy Farrell Contact Info: Phone: 219-218-0688 Email wf@willyfarrell.com Web: willyfarrell.com/coders

These programs should be understandable, adaptable, and, when appropriate, reusable. At the same time, the design and implementation of computer programs is used as a context for introducing other important aspects of computer science, including the development and analysis of algorithms, the development and use of fundamental data structures, the study of standard algorithms and typical applications, and the use of logic and formal methods. In addition, the responsible use of these systems is an integral part of the course. The topic outline on pages 810 summarizes the content typically taught in the AP Computer Science A course.

Students either attend morning classes from 7:35 - 9:15 AM or afternoon classes from 1:30 - 3:10 PM. Tuesdays are District PLC days and the schedule is 7:35 - 8:55 AM and 12:45 - 2:05 PM. Students may attend both sessions if their high school schedule permits. Students attend their home high school when not at the ITFP. Classes meet for the entire semester and are worth 10 credit points Once accepted into the program, students do not need to reapply. Accepted students can enter/exit the program at any time during their high school career.

name: Costa Ricas National Program of Educational Informatics MEP-FOD
levels: Preschool | Elementary | Middle School | High School | Vocational
description: The Omar Dengo Foundation of Costa Rica is a private, non-profit organization that since 1987 has developed and executed national projects in the fields of educational innovation and digital technologies in public schools with a distinctive use of coding (programming) as a central tool to stimulate creativity, thinking skills and problem-solving abilities in teachers, children and youth. The National Program of Educational Informatics of the Ministry of Public Education and the Omar Dengo Foundation (PRONIE MEP-FOD), that currently serves 512.232 students in 1,668 public elementary and high schools thorough the country, is strongly linked to the epistemological theories of Piaget and Vigotsky concerning social and cognitive development in individuals, and has based its pedagogical foundation on the constructionist theory of Dr. Seymour Papert. The Foundation, based on a constructivist approach to teaching and learning, introduced the use of computers in public schools in Costa Rica in 1988 to provide opportunities for children and youth to improve their capacities and computer programming has always been at the core of the programs activities. The Foundations programs have introduced programming throughout Costa Ricas public school system as a mean for children and youth to make representation and share personal interpretations of their knowledge and they have started programming computers from an early age. Teachers and researchers have been trained to facilitate computational thinking tasks and approaches proposed by researchers from MIT such as tinkering, debugging, remixing, abstraction, and use of modules. Elementary school children start by using tile programming interfaces (drag and drop) as a way to simplify syntax structure and help them understand algorithmic thinking. High-school age youth expand their programming experience with the use of open code writing (scripting) and object-oriented programming. Programming is then used as a powerful resource for developing abilities such as learning to reason logically and creatively, interactive resolution of problems, learning by design of robots, and teamwork. This special know-how has been of central importance for the development of a digital culture among Costa Rican children, youth and teachers, and for the attainment of significant levels of technology fluency and overall improved capacities.
