name: Borderless Education
description: This December, we would like to invite your child to take part in our "Creative Computing for Kids" pilot workshops conducted by Imperial College London graduates to help children discover their inner interest and passion in technology. Creative Computing for Kids is designed to make introduction to programming both easier and fun. By using a simplified visual programming system called Scratch, your child can explore and learn at their own pace and tackle problems through trial and error. It is a 4 session pilot workshops designed to give children aged between 8-13 an introduction to programming, inspired by the Code.org video featuring Bill Gates and Mark Zuckerberg. We believe that this early exposure gives kids an opportunity to discover themselves, nurture their natural curiosity while instilling the basic groundwork of computational thinking. Invitation Details Dates: Every Saturday in December 2013 (30th Nov, 7th, 14th & 21st), or Every Sunday in December 2013 (1st, 8th, 15th & 22nd) Times: Morning (10:00-12:30pm) for ages 8-13, Location: Starbucks @ TTDI, Grande Conference Room No. 20-G, Jalan Tun Mohd Fuad 1, Taman Tun Dr Ismail Fees: None. By invitation Requirements: Bring your own Laptop (and its power supply and mouse) To register a place, click on our website.

name: Dev Bootcamp (New York City)
description: Dev Bootcamp, founded in 2011, is the first short-term programming bootcamp designed to train world-class junior web developers and software engineers. Students spend 700+ hours over 9 weeks deliberately practicing the fundamentals of software engineering and web development using Ruby, Rails, HTML, CSS, SQL, and JavaScript. Our focus is on graduating engineers first and Rails-proficient web developers second. Within two months of graduation 90%+ of the students looking for jobs receive an offer with a median salary of $75k. Our alumni work at companies like Exec, Hipmunk, 1000memories, ThoughtBot, Pivotal Labs, TapJoy, Ouya, and The Climate Corporation. Think of it as a bootcamp-ified Montessori school or an apprenticeship of steroids. Some words from our students: * "DBC is the best learning environment that I have ever been in." (Student, Fall 2012) * "Dev Bootcamp has simply changed my entire life." (Student, Summer 2012) * "Dev Bootcamp was pretty much the best, most compact learning experience of my life." name: Sonoran Science Academy Phoenix
description: The AP Computer Science A course is an introductory course in computer science. Because the design and implementation of computer programs to solve problems involve skills that are fundamental to the study of computer science, a large part of the course is built around the development of computer programs that correctly solve a given problem. These programs should be understandable, adaptable, and, when appropriate, reusable. At the same time, the design and implementation of computer programs is used as a context for introducing other important aspects of computer science, including the development and analysis of algorithms, the development and use of fundamental data structures, the study of standard algorithms and typical applications, and the use of logic and formal methods

name: Creative Coding for Kids- After School & Day Camps
description: We teach kids ages 8-12 the joy of coding, by helping them write their own customized computer game! In addition to our summer camps, we now offer after-school programs at several Seattle Schools, plus all-day coding camps on certain "no school" days. Our unique games-centered approach is winning rave reviews from both kids and parents. We use Scratch, the MIT-developed tool created just for this purpose. Our philosophy: Today's computers are more like a box of crayons than a calculator. Major math skills are no longer required. The most important traits for coding today are CREATIVITY and PERSISTENCE. The key is to make it fun, start young, and encourage your child's work on their own pet projects, so they learn because they want to make their own thing awesome. It works brilliantly. Read reviews on our site. To see if we're teaching at your school, (or request that we come to you) please go to our website. The address given is our "No School" all-day camp location. Girls and boys are taught in a supportive, mutually respectful, fun environment. Classes offered for all skill levels and may be repeated to progress further. For up-to-date class dates, times, and schools served, visit us at http://www.creativecoding4kids.com

description: I am a certified teacher that works for Grand Rapids Public Schools, in a program called Shared Time. I currently service Anchor Point Christian and St. Anthony of Padua. I see children 1-2 times each week throughout the school year, and use classroom content for the basis of teaching technology skills. I teach Cyber Safety, Animation, Digital Photography, C.A.D., Desktop Publishing, Presentation, Skills review, Research, Engineering, Physics and Programing. The first and second graders I teach learn logo using the Roamer Robot and Roamer World software. I also use Lightbot and the online logo programing site for the youngest students. I use Toontalk programing for 3rd grade, for 4th grade I teach tesselations using Tesslemanic, 5th graders learn to program using Etoys sometimes called "Squeak",6th graders learn Scratch, 7th graders Alice and my 8th graders use HTML Kit to write code for webpages. All of these are free open source software which make it both practical and affordable to teach programing. Unfortunately none of the programs work on Ipad tablets, so as so many schools move to one to one tablets-it is going to even more difficult to teach programing. I am open to having others visit my classroom and even use the lessons on my wiki site to encourage the use of technology. So far I am hanging in there fighting the good fight even with all the state of Michigan cuts to education and decreases in pay.

description: We offer Technology Education at all grade levels as an exploratory class. The Technology Education Lab is set up for a modular rotation with an emphasis on exploring the many different areas of technology while also exposing students to the careers involved in those areas of technology. Students have the opportunity to create, build and complete hands on projects to reinforce fundamentals presented by each module. Each module station has a different focus area like: Aviation/Flight, Video Production, and Computer Numerical Controlled Mill and Lathe. The goal of Technology Education is to deliver technology content to students through the use of hands-on, project based assignments that allow them to see how machines, equipment, and software can be used to take an unfinished, raw material/product and turn it into a finished product. This process allows students to grasp main concepts to become Technologically Literate.

description: CyberPack project aims to develop creativity through the implementation of projects based on digital technologies used daily by young people ( sound, image, 3D , web, Twitter, Facebook , Kinect , etc.) It also aims to provide a framework facilitators / trainers / teachers who will implement these projects. Through a series of practical experiments with the increasing complexity , users will learn the basics of programming, develop logical thinking but also an artistic sense . For this, they discover the free software and open source Processing. It is used by young digital creators in the world and can address very quickly the real-time programming and therefore access to interactivity. It also allows the graphic design and geometry , 2D and 3D animation, sound generation , data processing and data visualization, facial recognition, physics, etc. . To assist users in their learning, CyberPack project provides them with : 1 . a toolkit based on the principle of learning by projects: it offers more than 10 exciting projects of increasing complexity in the field of image , audio , video , and interaction. Projects are accompanied by two booklets (one student booklet and a reference manual ) . No prerequisite is required. 2 . an online learning platform , using social networks to share experiences among organizations (questions, achievements , demonstration videos , etc. . ) (in progress) 3 . educational support for facilitators / trainers / teachers : sessions of discovery and use of the kit , training for users and / or students (initiation, lectures, courses , workshops, ... ) CyberPack project is supported by the AS- E as part of the call for projects CREATIVE PEOPLE organized under the Creative Wallonia program. It was designed by The Institute NUMEDIART UMONS , in collaboration with teachers in digital ARTS  and Arts Centre team Diffusion of Science and Technology UMONS .

We get to bring industry partners in for the day to watch and see what the future of IT looks like and how these graduating seniors are ready to work in their field. During the conference, we bus in girls over the two days, my senior web development students do the hospitality and implementation of the whole conference, my junior class does the website/tweeting/marketing of the event and teaches some of the workshops, and my sophomore class teaches workshops. name: kidOYO Kids Learning Code @ The Cradle of Aviation
description: Program Runs from Monday, February 17th thru Friday, February 21st, 2014. Join kidOYO Instructors in partnership with The Cradle of Aviation for this exciting 5 Day Winter Break event: Kids Learning Code! kidOYO focuses on introducing children at a very early age to computer science and engineering through hands-on learning projects integrated with computational problem solving challenges. In this unique "Kids Learning Code" program aimed at students aged 9-13, we will be introducing students to the mechanics of computational problem solving for any number of student-interest driven outcomes. Students interested in gaining computational thinking skills, learning to create computer programmed games, imagine interactive and animated stories, or prototype ideas generated from their imaginations using tools such as micro-circuits and the wildly popular 3D sandbox Minecraft will be among peers in this exciting and unique program. We will introduce kids 9-13 to creative tools that let their imaginations explore and pursure outcomes in a social context unlike anything else. Here, kids own their own education. Students will receive a kidOYO USB flash drive and a kidOYO Tshirt. About kidOYO kidOYO produces innovative entrepreneurial ed-tech programs for students and teachers in multiple settings and formats. In-school K-12 programs, after-school programs, professional development programs, library programs, University-based programs, online-only programs, summer camps and monthly clubs offer many ways of getting involved with kidOYO. Leadership sets kidOYO apart; our team is composed of professional toy and technology developers and entrepreneurs who do what they teach, and bring real world context to the programs they develop to get students learning by doing. Learn more about kidOYO here: www.kidOYO.com/about

name: kidOYO @ Manhasset Library
description: Manhasset SEPTA's Gifted & Talented Division Presents..... kidOYO Code Dojo In this age-appropriate "Kids Learning Code" program, kidOYO instructors will walk students through the process of learning object oriented programming as they engage computational problem solving challenges. Students will complete the program with a working video game to take home with them as well as the software to continue to imagine, create and share! Students will learn about working with game character development, background stage and costume design basics. They will gain an understanding of controlling movements and using algorithms to write script which will result in multiple computer-based games to take home and continue their work. Ages 7-10 Students will require a USB Flash drive to save their work to. USBs will be available for purchase for $10 each at the event, or students may bring their own from home.

name: Coding Campus - Dojo Dev Camp
description: Introduction to Web Development Total Clock Hours: 135 Available Track: Part-time ~9 Weeks, 15hs/Week Required Supplies: Laptop computer no more than 3 years old with at least 4 Gigs of RAM. Coding Campus Introduction to Web Development Course provides introductory training in front end development with a brief overview of back end. Students are trained in HTML, CSS and Javascript with an introduction to Python. This course will prepare the student with the skills necessary to work as a frontend developer, with a basic understanding of back end software programming. The average front end developer in Utah earns an annual salary between $49K-$90K. Completion of this course will require at least 90% attendance and a brief, final portfolio presentation during the last week of the course. Coding Campus adheres to a Pass/Fail grading policy. Graduates of this course will receive an Introduction to Web Development certificate of completion. The introductory course builds a solid foundation for students completely new to computer programming and is an optional prerequisite to the Advanced Web Development course. Advanced Web Development Total Clock Hours: 360 Available Tracks: Full-Time ~9 weeks, 40hs/Week, Part-Time Day and Part-Time Evening ~18 weeks each, 20hs/Week Required Supplies: Laptop computer no more than 3 years old with at least 4 Gigs of RAM. The Advanced Web Development course is an in-depth approach to backend development with front end review and additional training in web development best-practices. Students are trained in HTML, CSS, Javascript, Python, and are instructed in using popular web development tools, Configuration Management, and cloud computing. This course will prepare the student for a career in back end web development. The average Back-end developer in Utah earns an annual salary between $55K-$90K. Completion of this course will require at least 90% attendance and a brief, final portfolio presentation during the last week of the course. Coding Campus adheres to a Pass/Fail grading policy. Graduates of this course will receive an Advanced Web Development certificate of completion.

The Registrar is responsible to the Rector for the day-to-day administration of the Polytechnic. name: Code Phreaks
description: Code Phreaks is a Chicago-based programming club that meets every Saturday between 10:00-12:00 at the Northtown branch of the Chicago Public Library. Our members work on computer game design, robotics, animations, and a variety of other multimedia projects. Creativity and collaboration are among the core values shared by our members as we transform our meeting space each week into a unique maker space where imagination meets invention. We also host occasional gaming events, Robocode tournaments, and coding dojos. We offer regular coding workshops that focus upon the Scratch, Alice, Starlogo, and Greenfoot environments, in addition to workshops that focus upon mobile app development using Java or App Inventor. Each year we host International Scratch Day in Chicago, he largest event in the Midwest celebrating Scratch, the programming environment developed at MIT's Media Lab. Membership is open to anyone from Chicago's north side in grades 5 - 12. Code Phreaks was formerly known as the Game Design Club (www.gamedesignclub.org), a program of Game Maker Academy, established in 2007.

name: TechSmartKids
description: C101- C103: Introduction to Coding I - III This is an advanced introduction to coding course using Scratch, an event-driven visual drag & drop programming language developed by MIT Media Lab. This course is offered through a series of three 10-12 week classes: - C101- Intro to Coding I - C102- Intro to Coding II - C103- Intro to Coding III and is available for following grade levels: - Grades 2-3 - Grades 4-5 - Grades 6-8 at the following locations: - Bellevue - Mercer Island - Redmond - Seattle This course will focus on fundamental computer science concepts including: * Commands * Sequences * Loops * Events * Parallelism * Advanced Conditionals * Advanced Operators * User interface controls * Data- built-in variables * Data- custom variables * Data- operators with variables * Data- Custom lists * Custom Blocks Fundamental programming concepts and best practices will be introduced as kids develop interactive computer programs. Kids will learn to think creatively and solve problems. Kids learn to be Product Thinkers Throughout the entire course kids learn how to bring their own ideas from inception to realization in a structured way using best practices of product development. As Product Thinkers kids will learn to begin with the end in mind. They will learn how to shape their ideas into products and break their products down into features and functionality. Every product has a user and every user has an experience with a product. As Product Thinkers kids will learn to care deeply about this experience. About TechSmartKids TechSmartKids is a fast-paced technology company based in Bellevue, WA. We are a group of passionate product managers, software & hardware engineers, designers, curriculum developers and teachers. We believe that if it can be imagined it can be made. Our passion is to inspire kids to see things differently and to believe that they can change the world through technology. We develop technology curriculum and courseware in computer science & hardware engineering and offer courses for elementary and middle school students. We guide, mentor and teach kids (ages 6 to 14 years old) to imagine, define, design, prototype and build innovative software and hardware products, unleashing their curiosity and imagination, helping them to become the Coders and Makers of tomorrow - the Next Generation to change the world.

name: Coding Dojo
description: Coding Dojo offers 12 Week Intensive Bootcamp in Seattle and Silicon Valley. We are teaching HTML, CSS, JavaScript, MySQL, PHP, OOP, MVC, Ajax, Ruby on Rails, Node.js, and much more. Our first "bootcamps" over three years ago were actually to train our own developers (we have about 11 developers now). Much of our bootcamp course content was derived from many iterations of training them to build advanced web applications over a few months at a time. In the fall of 2012 we began a part-time bootcamp rotation targeted at working professionals and entrepreneurs. We were extremely pleased with the results, and began the full-time bootcamp beginning in early 2013. During the course, students will study within our custom-built LMS (learning management system), where course contents and assignments are stored. They spend at least 50-70 hours a week coding with dedicated peers and expert mentors at their side to guide them.

name: The Buckley School
description: Introduction To Programming. This class introduces programming and algorithms to students who have a serious interest in learning the principles of computer science and programming. Topics covered include algorithms, reading values from the keyboard, printing values on the screen, iterative Java statements, understanding multiple data types, arrays, strings, functions, and other Java methods using the Eclipse Programming environment. Lab assignments are used to explain and explore programming concepts. This project-based class allows the students practice important problem solving techniques that become imperative at the next level of computer science. Mobile App Development: In the past years at Buckley, we have offered courses that introduce kids to programming through programs such as Scratch or Alice. While these programs have proven to be effective, they offer no incentive to continue on in programming or any other computer science course and we must stay on the cutting edge. This class will use the iOS environment, X-Code, C++ and the App developer kit to allow students to develop an application for either the iPhone or the iPad using code and a graphical user interface in a virtual environment. At the end of the year, students will have a working functional application that can be installed and run on a physical device.

name: Innovate Tacoma
description: We believe in inspiring 21st century innovators through project-based and place-based learning that will build expertise in critical thinking and problem solving. We believe in making of young people who will change the world. Project-Based Learning is a dynamic approach to teaching in which students explore real world problems and challenges, simultaneously developing cross curriculum skills while working in small collaborative groups. (The George Lucas Educational Foundation) Place-Based Learning immerses students in local heritage, culture, landscapes, opportunities, and experiences as a foundation for the study of language arts, mathematics, social studies, science, and other subjects. Place-based education encourages teachers and students to use the schoolyard, community, public lands, and other special places as resources, turning communities into classrooms. (Place-Based Education Collaborative. In Wheeler, G., Bergsman, K., Thumlert, C and Kelly, B. (2010). Sustainable Design Project Teacher Manual. Olympia, WA: Office of Superintendent of Public Education) because knowledge is available on every Internet-connected device, what you know matters far less than what you can do with what you know. The capacity to innovate  the ability to solve problems creatively or bring new possibilities to life  and skills like critical thinking, communication and collaboration are far more important than academic knowledge. As one executive told me, We can teach new hires the content, and we will have to because it continues to change, but we cant teach them how to think  to ask the right questions  and to take initiative. Tony Wagner, Author of Creating Innovators

name: Florida State University
description: Computer Science is a science but also a (liberal) art. There is a lot of diversity in practice for graduates in Computer Science. Software is used and written across a wide range of industries. Virtually every organization needs "coders" to develop and maintain software and systems. Computer Science is also an exceptionally fast-moving field. The department offers technical instruction that stays on the cutting edge of new developments while simultaneously providing each student with a core of intellectual tools that will never become obsolete. The department has a number of active research programs across the spectrum of computing, including: computer architecture, compilers, networks and tools for distributed applications, parallel computation, databases and data mining, operating systems, algorithms, scientific problem solving environments, large-scale scientific computation and databases, computer and network security (including cryptography), computer forensics, computer vision, applied computational geometry, random number generation and Monte Carlo methods, as well as applications of fuzzy relations and non-classical logics. These research programs enjoy external support from agencies ranging from the National Science Foundation to the private sector. The Department of Computer Science offers undergraduate and graduate programs leading to the Bachelor of Science (BS) and Bachelor of Arts (BA) degrees, and the Master of Science (MS) and Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) degrees in Computer Science. The BS in CS degree program at FSU is nationally accredited by the ABET Computer Accreditation Commission. The department also trains security specialists under the Committee of National Security Systems (CNSS) standards NSTISSI standard 4011 "Information Security Professionals." As of August 2008, the university is also certified to offer the additional professional standard of CNSS 4014 for "Information Security Officers." Representative jobs for employees with Computer Science degrees are Software Engineer, Cyber Security Specialist, Web Developer, Programmer, Computer Systems Analyst, Database Administrator, Network and Computer Systems Administrator.

name: TechKnowHow Summer Camps - Arduino & Unity
description: The Arduino Electronics & Unity 3D Game Design course provides a thorough introduction to electronics and computer programming using the Arduino and UnityScript languages, which are similar to C/C++ and JavaScript, respectively. In the mornings, students learn the fundamentals of electronic circuit design by building and programming Arduino projects, including color-changing lights, a 2-player game, and a game controller compatible with Unity. The Arduino is a programmable microcontroller that allows users to control custom-built electronics with a computer and vice versa. In the afternoons, students create their own games using Unity, a game engine used by professional developers and universities throughout the world. Students write scripts that control player and enemy movements, change levels, generate objects, track health, and much more! Week-long classes offered in Burlingame, Campbell, Fremont, Palo Alto, Pleasanton, and Sunnyvale.

description: Introduction to Java Dive right in to coding with Java, one of the worlds most scalable and popular programming languages. This is a practical and fun workshop with no lecture-style teaching. You will be coding progressively trickier problems for the entire duration of the class. You will learn by doing. Youll practice the basics of programming  variables, control statements, loops and boolean logic  that will provide you with a solid foundation for tackling new technologies and programming languages. This knowledge will be absorbed by constructively coding for the entire duration of the class. Well build 2-3 small applications each day that perform animation and user interaction tasks using Java. Youll leave with the tools you need to build your own Java applications at home or with your classmates. You dont need to be a techie to enjoy this workshop. Programming is easy and fun.

name: George Mason University - AspireIT Camp using Kodu
description: This workshop based class, sponsored by the National Center for Women & Information Technology, is targeted towards middle-school girls. No previous computer knowledge, interest, or skills are required as the course is intended to give girls a heightened sense of confidence around computers and technology using Microsoft's easy to learn software, Kodu, to design and develop fun video games for the computer and Surface tablets. The girls will also learn about famous women all throughout STEM in order to take on positive role models to help them feel comfortable in a field that is considered to be dominated by men. The intention of the class is to hopefully give our students the spark they need in order to develop a life-long passion and interest in STEM hobbies and topics so as to increase the amount of women in the field's future.

name: Program yoUr Future
description: Program yoUr Future, a non-profit outreach program, aims to raise greater awareness for women in technology by complimenting San Francisco Bay Area middle school girls education with programming basics using AppInventor and Scratch, networking skills, valuable mentorship opportunities, and fieldtrips to local museums or tech companies. PUF will also cover topics, including How to Write a Resume, STEM Year-long Opportunities, and High School Success & Leadership. Participants will also interact with and learn from IT and STEM mentors and key note speakers AND participate in mock interviews. Through fun CS-related hands-on activities, they will not only have the opportunity to explore interdisciplinary applications and acquire presentation skills but will also be able to keep their creation as a souvenir! The participants are also challenged to identify a social issue or problem and design a solution integrating the use of information technology. No programming experience or prior computer science knowledge is necessary to participate! The girls will form a strong community and enduring friendships! Students will also have the opportunity to receive prizes and scholarship money! PUF also trains a High School Leadership Team! Apply to PUF now! ROLLING ADMISSIONS until March 31, 2014!
languages: Arduino | Java | Logo | Mobile Apps | Scratch

name: Dave Briccettis Young Programmers
description: Computer programming classes for young programmers in grades 312, in or near Lafayette, run by experienced software developer and teacher Dave Briccetti. Sessions usually consist of instruction, coding time, and a lot of collaboration and learning from each other. Kids will bring a laptop, and learn to program computers using languages like Scratch, Python and JavaScript. Some sessions will be free, but most will have a fee. For kids-only sessions (most of them), parents may observe if space permits.
languages: Javascript | Kojo | Making a graphical web game | Pygame | Python | Scala | Scratch

name: Trinity University
description: TECH Camps, which stands for Trinity Encouraging Computing for Her is comprised of two Saturday events and one weekend retreat. Girls will learn how to create an Android app using MIT's App Inventor, explore wearable technology, and create 3D Printed objects

name: Robot Springboard Technology Camp @ Drexel University (An NCWIT AspireIT Program)
description: Robot Springboard Technology Camp @ Drexel University is a one week program for middle school girls which includes work with robotics, programming and leadership skills. The course will be held August 4th-8th and is designed for students without any prior experience working with technology. At lunchtime participants will get to meet and hear life experiences of women working in technology fields in Philadelphia. The camp concludes on Friday with a "Technology Showcase" where participants will get to demonstrate their newly acquired robotics and computing skills to their family. All snacks, lunches, and a light dinner at the Technology Showcase are included in the $50 program fee. Robot Springboard gratefully acknowledges both The College of Computing and Informatics at Drexel University and NCWIT (The National Center for Women and Information Technology) in helping to support this program.

name: Ampersand school---Girlz Tech Starter---Aspire IT
description: Girlz tech starter gives middle school girls a taste of app making. In this week long App making camp, the girls will use app inventor to create apps for the Google play store. They will also learn about jobs in STEM fields and learn about robotics and 3d printing.

Two half-day sessions are offered: Programming and Game Design from 8:30am - 11:30am, and Robotics from 12:00pm - 3:00pm. This four-day summer enrichment program on the campus of St. John Vianney High School will provide young learners entering the 6th-8th grade with an opportunity to explore several aspects of programming, game design, circuitry and robotics. This second year of GTA offers a host of engaging activities that will interest students new to GTA as well as those who attended last year.

name: Young Women in Computing
description: YWiC summer camps provide a fresh and fun way to bring Computer Science (CS) to young women through informal education opportunities. YWiC brings performance and outcome potential in computing through the instruction of software platforms and hopefully build on the interest and fascination for technology that we all share! This fantastic program grew through the passion and commitment of undergraduate near-peers who serve as the mentors and connectors to CS. The expansion of YWiC into a multidimensional outreach program has directly impacted almost 9,000 students across the state! Our FREE YWiC summer, day camps will be hosted in June and held in Las Cruces on the New Mexico State University campus. We welcome applicants from out-of-town, but we do not provide housing or accommodations. Camps run from 9:00am-3:30pm, lunch is included. For the summer of 2014, middle and high school participants could be exposed to the following platforms: LilyPad Arduino LiveCode Scratch Programming Greenfoot Binary Code Google Drive Pencil Code LEGO Mindstorm NXT Robotics HTML, Website Development w jGRASP Python Linux and Bash Commands Ruby CS Unplugged Careers in Computing It's going to a fun and challenging summer! We can't wait! Middle School camps for girls: June 2 - 6, 2014 June 9 - 13, 2014 July 13 - 19, 2014 High School camps for girls: June 16 - 20, 2014 June 23 - 27, 2014
